# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: home-sports
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:home-sports/2005-new-orleans-saints-season] The 2005 season was the New Orleans Saints' 39th in the National Football League (NFL) and the sixth and final under head coach Jim Haslett.
[src:home-sports/2005-new-orleans-saints-season] The season began with the team trying to improve from their 8–8 record from 2004.
[src:home-sports/2005-new-orleans-saints-season] The Saints played two preseason games in the Louisiana Superdome before being forced to evacuate New Orleans due to Hurricane Katrina.
[src:home-sports/2005-new-orleans-saints-season] They were forced to play the rest of the season on the road, splitting their games between their temporary headquarters at San Antonio’s Alamodome, and LSU’s Tiger Stadium in Baton Rouge, and even playing their first home game at Giants Stadium.
[src:home-sports/2005-new-orleans-saints-season] The season ended with a 3–13 record, their equal-worst record alongside 1996 and 1999 since their 1–15 1980 season, and the firing of Jim Haslett.
[src:home-sports/2005-new-orleans-saints-season] He was replaced by Sean Payton the following season.
[src:home-sports/2005-new-orleans-saints-season] This was also Aaron Brooks' last season as the Saints’ quarterback, as he was released during the offseason and replaced by future hall of famer Drew Brees in the same season Sean Payton was hired.
[src:home-sports/2005-new-orleans-saints-season] Despite being played at Giants Stadium, this was officially a home game for the Saints as the Louisiana Superdome was being used as an emergency shelter in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.
[src:home-sports/2005-new-orleans-saints-season] The Saints out gained the Giants, finishing the game with 422 yards of total offense compared to New York's 257.
[src:home-sports/2005-new-orleans-saints-season] However, the Saints' offense also committed six turnovers that resulted in 17 points for the Giants.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The fourth meeting of the G20 heads of state/government, to discuss the global financial system and the world economy, took place at the Metro Toronto Convention Centre in Toronto, Ontario, Canada, on 26–27 June 2010.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The summit's priorities included evaluating the progress of financial reform, developing sustainable stimulus measures, debating global bank tax, and promoting open markets.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Alongside the twenty-one representatives of the G20 major economies, leaders of six invited nations, and eight additional intergovernmental organizations also took part in the summit.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Prior to the summit, Canadian Prime Minister Stephen Harper announced that the theme would be "recovery and new beginnings," referring to an anticipated economic stimulus from the impact of the ongoing world recession.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Harper initially proposed to hold the summit in Huntsville, Ontario, where the 36th G8 summit was scheduled immediately prior.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Organizers later deemed the town insufficient to provide hospitality for the large number of G20 delegates and journalists, favouring Toronto as the host location.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Organizers formed an Integrated Security Unit, consisting of police officers from several regional departments, to provide security during the summit in Downtown Toronto.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The event was part of the largest and most expensive security operation in Canadian history.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Many hundreds of members of the public were wrongfully detained, some held in inhumane conditions.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The total combined cost between the 36th G8 summit in Huntsville and the G20 summit in Toronto including security, infrastructure, and hospitality, was determined to be approximately C$858 million.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Many leaders of the G20 disagreed about which issues should be discussed at the summit.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The prime focus of the summit discussions was the recovery from the ongoing global recession and the European debt crisis.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Summit leaders were divided over which strategies would be best for tackling these problems.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The European Union emphasized the need to cut their deficits by focusing on austerity measures.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] In contrast, the United States emphasized the importance of maintaining economic stimulus spending in order to encourage growth.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] In summit discussions, the countries of the European Union explained projected reductions in spending and balanced budgets.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Alternatively, China, India, and the United States argued in favor of increased stimulus funding to mitigate the effects of recession.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Among the specifics proposed by the European Union were a global bank tax and a Robin Hood tax, but the United States and Canada opposed these plans.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Other topics of concern were international development and continuing international aid to Africa and other developing nations.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Some invitees expressed criticism of Israel's Gaza strip blockade and of the nuclear programs of North Korea and the United States raised issues of corruption and security in Afghanistan.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Security officials began preparing for summit security in Toronto in February 2010.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The five departments formed an Integrated Security Unit (ISU), similar to the one created for the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Calgary Police Service supplied 150 volunteer police officers a week before the summit.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] According to an early estimate by *The Globe and Mail*, 25,000 uniformed police officers, 1,000 security guards from Commissionaires Great Lakes, and several Canadian military forces were to be deployed during the summit.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The North American Aerospace Defense Command (NORAD) conducted Amalgam Virgo exercises on May 6 and 7 across the Greater Toronto Area using CF-18 Hornet jets, CH-124 Sea Kings, and CH-146 Griffon helicopters at low altitudes.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The total cost for security at both the G8 and the G20 summits was determined to be $1.8 billion, paid entirely by the federal Crown-in-Council, excluding the costs of any possible damage to local business.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The ISU created a security perimeter, beginning with the outer boundary, specifically bordered by King Street to the north, Lake Shore Boulevard to the south, Yonge Street to the east, and Spadina Avenue to the west, where vehicles would be restricted during the summit dates.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The area surrounding the Metro Toronto Convention Centre itself was fenced and off-limits to civilians and protesters.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The 3-metre (10 ft) high fence, contracted to SNC-Lavalin by Public Works and Government Services Canada and installed by two Gormley, Ontario-based companies, was built at a cost of $5.5-million and installation began on June 7.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The Toronto Police Service installed 77 additional closed-circuit television security cameras in the area and purchased four Long Range Acoustic Devices which were to be in use exclusively during the summit.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The ISU decided on also using water cannons for riot control.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The security perimeter even extended into the waters of Lake Ontario and included a Maritime Security Operation with numerous Police vessels and the Canadian Coast Guard Ship Griffon patrolling to discourage international demonstrators from unlawful entry into Canada.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] A former film studio located on Eastern Avenue was designated as a temporary detention centre for individuals arrested during the summit.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Toronto Police Service announced that Trinity Bellwoods Park would be the designated protest area, but following opposition from local residents, police relocated the designated protest zone to the northern part of Queen's Park.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Canada Post declared that it would remove post boxes in the security zone.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Toronto Parking Authority removed some parking meters as well.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Small trees along sidewalks around the convention centre were removed to prevent them from being used as weapons by protesters.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Other removed municipal properties include 745 newspaper boxes, 200 public trash cans, 70 mailboxes, 29 bus shelters, and 5 public information boards.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Canada's largest banks, which are headquartered in Downtown Toronto, made plans to have employees work at alternate sites outside their downtown facilities, such as at home or in other branches.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The Liquor Control Board of Ontario (LCBO) announced the closure of seven liquor stores in the downtown core during the summit as a precaution to looting.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The PATH, CN Tower, University of Toronto, Art Gallery of Ontario, and the Ontario Legislative Building were also closed to public during the summit dates.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Mirvish Productions cancelled performances of two musicals at its theatres, *Rock of Ages* and *Mamma Mia!*, during the week of the summit.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Similarly, the Factory Theatre cancelled shows during the summit week.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Highway 427 and the Gardiner Expressway, the route from Toronto Pearson International Airport in Mississauga to the Convention Centre in downtown, periodically closed down for motorcades, and police jammed wireless reception along the two highways.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Exits to Yonge Street and Bay Street from the Gardiner Expressway were closed during the summit dates.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Toronto Transit Commission announced that subway stations near the convention centre would remain open and operational, despite some detoured bus routes and the closure of Queens Quay Station.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Via Rail announced that it would not operate at Union Station during the summit dates, instead providing shuttle bus service from the Yorkdale and Scarborough Centre bus terminals to the Brampton and Oshawa stations respectively.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Nav Canada announced that it would place restrictions on the airspace in Toronto, making it limited to commercial flights only while all others would be restricted within a 30-nautical-mile (56 km) radius.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Porter Airlines received permission to continue flights to and from Billy Bishop Toronto City Airport.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The Toronto District School Board and Toronto Catholic District School Board cancelled school bus services to six Downtown schools on June 25, affecting 45,000 students, 10,000 of whom were physically disabled.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Summit organizers established a media centre for international media personnel, journalists, and press reporters at the Direct Energy Centre at the Exhibition Place.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The Federal and Ontario governments constructed a 20,000-square-foot (1,858 m2) pavilion, called *Experience Canada* or *Canadian Corridor* in the media centre to promote Canadian tourism internationally.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The *Northern Ontario Oasis* included donated canoes, a shoreline with deck chairs for journalists to cool off, and a mobile phone recharging station.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The background was a large screen that portrayed various images of the Muskoka region.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The cost of the international media centre, the *Experience Canada* pavilion, and artificial lake, which were $23 million, $1.9 million, and $57,000 respectively, was the target of controversies.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Participants of the Toronto summit were announced by Stephen Harper on May 8, 2010.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Harper extended invitations to the leaders of Ethiopia and Malawi to further represent the continent of Africa along with South Africa, a G20 member.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] He also invited leaders of the Netherlands, Spain, Vietnam, and Nigeria.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Toronto Pearson International Airport was the port of entry for delegates attending both the G8 and G20 summits.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] French president Nicolas Sarkozy and Chinese president Hu Jintao were the first of the G20 leaders to arrive.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The arrival of Hu coincided with his state visit to Canada, hosted by Governor General of Canada Michaëlle Jean in Ottawa.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Presidents Jacob Zuma of South Africa and Goodluck Jonathan of Nigeria arrived on June 24.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] British prime minister David Cameron arrived on June 25, following a short visit in Halifax to celebrate the centennial of the Canadian Forces Maritime Command.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Remaining leaders with the G8 also arrived on the same day.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development and the International Labour Organization, as well as Ethiopia, Malawi, Nigeria, and Vietnam made their first G20 summit appearances in Toronto.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Recently designated heads of government, namely Cameron and Japanese prime minister Naoto Kan, made the G8 and G20 summits their first international conferences.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Australia's deputy prime minister, Wayne Swan, attended the summit on behalf of Julia Gillard, whose appointment as prime minister occurred on June 24.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Brazilian president Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva cancelled his trip to remain in his country due to the then-recent flooding in Northeastern Brazil; in his place, Guido Mantega, Brazil's finance minister, headed the nation's delegation.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] After the G8 summit in Huntsville, Ontario ended, Cameron, whose aircraft was grounded due to weather conditions, shared transportation to Toronto in Marine One with US President, Barack Obama.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Major protests occurred in downtown Toronto during the week of the summit, which abruptly escalated during the days of the summit.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Early opposition to the G20 included an incident in Ottawa where a bank was firebombed by anarchists, who claimed they would be present during the G20 summit in Toronto.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The perceived security threat caused the Integrated Security Unit to increase security measures.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Protests began one week ahead of the summit, organized by groups including Oxfam Canada and the Ontario Coalition Against Poverty.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Issues such as poverty, gay rights, capitalism and globalization, indigenous rights, and controversial issues with the summit itself were the object of protests.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Despite a few arrests, protests over the week were mainly determined to be peaceful.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] As the first day of the summit approached, protesters grew in numbers.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Several streets were closed to demonstrations on the debut of the summit.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Peaceful protests were followed by black bloc tactics as individuals dressed in black dispersed from the crowd and began damaging the windows of particular businesses across downtown Toronto, mostly fast food chains, retail stores and banks, as well as local businesses.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Police cruisers were set on fire and vehicles of media corporations were damaged.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Nearby hospitals, shopping centres, and hotels were put in lockdown mode while public transit services were diverted from downtown to other locations.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] As security was further tightened and forces increased in presence the following day, protests against police brutality occurred in front of the Eastern Avenue temporary detention centre, where nearly 500 arrested individuals were kept from the previous day's riots.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] A group of protesters was also "kettled" for around four-and-a-half hours, including a severe rainstorm after black bloc protesters were believed to be in the crowd.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Over 1100 people were confirmed to be arrested over the week.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The ISU performed sweeping arrests within a specific boundary from the summit venue.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Individuals arrested during the protests condemned the treatment they received from police.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Ultimately, a constable would be convicted of assaulting a protestor and a superintendent of unlawful arrest and discreditable conduct for ordering the "kettling" incidents; both received notional punishments and kept their police jobs.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Prior to the Toronto summit, it was speculated that it would not see the same outcome as previous summits.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] This was partially due to most countries' entering recovery mode from the global economic recession after the past G20 summits; thus, the likelihood of new issues being raised was minimal.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] During the working dinner for G20 leaders on the evening of June 26, South African president [Jacob Zuma] promoted more partnership between the international community and Africa for the development in the continent.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] "As Africa we bring to the G20 Summit the key message that we must, together as the developing and developed worlds, promote stronger and more effective and equal international partnerships for growth and development," he remarked.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] At the summit, the US president Barack Obama warned that global recovery was still "fragile." In hopes of boosting American exports, he proposed a free trade agreement between the United States and South Korea.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] A key agreement the leaders of developed nations made was to cut annual budget deficits in half by 2013.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The leaders also agreed on reducing debt-to-GDP ratio in each economy by 2016.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The debate on imposing a tax on financial institutions was settled as the group agreed that financial institutions would be required to make fair contributions to recover costs from the financial sector reform, but the manner of collecting the contributions would be left to each government.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Participants also decided that the institutions would be required to keep a higher amount of financial capital in case of future financial shocks.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Climate change and food security were also discussed; the leaders reiterated their commitment to a "greener growth".
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The financial costs of hosting the G8 and G20 summits was the topic of several political debates and the target of criticism by local groups.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The reasons for the large price for both summits were questioned by some politicians and local groups.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Members of Parliament Olivia Chow and Mark Holland labelled the initially claimed budget of $1.1-billion for hosting the summits as "obscene" and "insane" while others argued that the money could have been used for long-pending municipal projects in Canada, such as Transit City.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The security cost for the two summits was believed to be more expensive than the combined security costs of the 2010 Winter Olympics and Paralympics in Vancouver and Whistler, British Columbia, which were $878 million.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] However, according to final calculations from the House of Commons of Canada as of October 2010, the exact cost for holding both summits was $857,901,850.31, making it less expensive than the security costs for the 2010 Winter Olympics.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] It was initially claimed that the summits stand as the most expensive ever held, with security costs for the London and Pittsburgh reported as having been only $30 million and $18 million, respectively.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Ward Elcock, former Canadian Security Intelligence Service director and the chief of the Integrated Security Units for the Winter Olympics and the G8/G20 summits, claimed that the security costs were in fact "comparable" with those of previous summits.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Finance minister Jim Flaherty defended the security cost, claiming "it's necessary to spend substantially to have security.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Some protesting groups gave names to the artificial lake, such as "Harper's Folly".
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] New Democratic Party leader Jack Layton condemned the Harper government, saying, "we've got a government here that has to create an artificial lake when Canada has more lakes than just about any other country in the world.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Harper also defended by saying, "This is a classic attempt for us to be able to market the country." Upon its opening, the artificial lake received mostly negative reviews from Canadian reporters.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The summit's economic impact was a major concern of a few local politicians and citizens.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] The City of Toronto government, as well as some public representatives, previously argued that the G20 summit should be held at an isolated venue, such as the Exhibition Place, rather than the Metro Toronto Convention Centre, which is located in the city's central business district.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] As a result, during the aftermath of the protests during the summit, when several business and properties in Downtown Toronto were damaged, mayor David Miller urged the federal government to compensate for all the damages.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] It was initially outlined by the government that only damages to businesses within the security zone would be compensated.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] However, all damages occurred outside of the security zone.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Some businesses in the downtown core suffered financially as a result.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] On June 17, the United States Department of State issued a travel alert for Toronto, warning tourists of the expected traffic disruptions and potentially violent protests during the G20 summit.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] During the summit, a few overseas reporters commented on Canada and the summits.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] A reporter of the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) made positive remarks about Canada's economy, saying "The Canadians, it seems, have answers for even the toughest puzzles and they are keen to share their strategies with the rest of the world.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Why in this economy, we all want to be Canadian." A writer in *The New York Times* made positive comments about the summits' preparations and natural beauty of the Muskoka region.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] *The Times of India* and *The Hindu* commented on impacts on city life in Toronto due to the G20 summit and the "unprecedented" security measures taken in Canada.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] A Reuters reporter, on the other hand, condemned the international media centre's artificial lake.
[src:home-sports/2010-toronto-g-20-summit] Looking forward, French president Nicolas Sarkozy announced that the costs for hosting the proposed 2011 G20 Cannes summit and 37th G8 summit in France would be one-tenth of Canada's.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] As a medication, it is used to treat several conditions, including allergic reaction anaphylaxis, cardiac arrest, and superficial bleeding.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Inhaled adrenaline may be used to improve the symptoms of croup.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] It may also be used for asthma when other treatments are not effective.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] It is given intravenously, by injection into a muscle, by inhalation, or by injection just under the skin.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Common side effects include shakiness, anxiety, and sweating.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] A fast heart rate and high blood pressure may occur.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Occasionally it may result in an abnormal heart rhythm.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] While the safety of its use during pregnancy and breastfeeding is unclear, the benefits to the mother must be taken into account.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] A case has been made for the use of adrenaline infusion in place of the widely accepted treatment of inotropes for preterm infants with clinical cardiovascular compromise.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Although sufficient data strongly recommends adrenaline infusions as a viable treatment, more trials are needed to conclusively determine that these infusions will successfully reduce morbidity and mortality rates among preterm, cardiovascularly compromised infants.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Epinephrine can also be used to treat open-angle glaucoma, as it increases the outflow of aqueous humor from the eye, which lowers intraocular pressure.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The adrenal medulla is a major contributor to total circulating catecholamines (L-DOPA is at a higher concentration in the plasma), though it contributes over 90% of circulating adrenaline.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Little adrenaline is found in other tissues, mostly in scattered chromaffin cells and in a small number of neurons that use adrenaline as a neurotransmitter.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Following adrenalectomy, adrenaline disappears below the detection limit in the bloodstream.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Pharmacological doses of adrenaline stimulate α1, α2, β1, β2, and β3 adrenoceptors of the sympathetic nervous system.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Sympathetic nerve receptors are classified as adrenergic, based on their responsiveness to adrenaline.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The term "adrenergic" is often misinterpreted in that the main sympathetic neurotransmitter is noradrenaline, rather than adrenaline, as discovered by Ulf von Euler in 1946.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenaline has a β2 adrenoceptor-mediated effect on metabolism and the airway, with no direct neural connection from the sympathetic ganglia to the airway.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Walter Bradford Cannon originally proposed the concept of the adrenal medulla and the sympathetic nervous system being involved in the flight, fight, and fright response.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] But the adrenal medulla, in contrast to the adrenal cortex, is not required for survival.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] In adrenalectomized patients, hemodynamic and metabolic responses to stimuli such as hypoglycemia and exercise remain normal.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] One physiological stimulus to adrenaline secretion is exercise.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] This was first demonstrated by measuring the dilation of a (denervated) pupil of a cat on a treadmill, later confirmed using a biological assay of urine samples.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Biochemical methods for measuring catecholamines in plasma were published from 1950 onwards.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Although much valuable work has been published using fluorimetric assays to measure total catecholamine concentrations, the method is too non-specific and insensitive to accurately determine the very small quantities of adrenaline in plasma.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The development of extraction methods and enzyme–isotope derivate radio-enzymatic assays (REA) transformed the analysis down to a sensitivity of 1 pg for adrenaline.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Early REA plasma assays indicated that adrenaline and total catecholamines rise late in exercise, mostly when anaerobic metabolism commences.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] During exercise, the adrenaline blood concentration rises partially from the increased secretion of the adrenal medulla and partly from the decreased metabolism of adrenaline due to reduced blood flow to the liver.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Infusion of adrenaline to reproduce exercise circulating concentrations of adrenaline in subjects at rest has little hemodynamic effect other than a slight β2-mediated fall in diastolic blood pressure.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Infusion of adrenaline well within the physiological range suppresses human airway hyper-reactivity sufficiently to antagonize the constrictor effects of inhaled histamine.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] A link between the sympathetic nervous system and the lungs was shown in 1887 when Grossman showed that stimulation of cardiac accelerator nerves reversed muscarine-induced airway constriction.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] In experiments in the dog, where the sympathetic chain was cut at the level of the diaphragm, Jackson showed that there was no direct sympathetic innervation to the lung, but bronchoconstriction was reversed by the release of adrenaline from the adrenal medulla.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] An increased incidence of asthma has not been reported for adrenalectomized patients; those with a predisposition to asthma will have some protection from airway hyper-reactivity from their corticosteroid replacement therapy.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Exercise induces progressive airway dilation in normal subjects that correlates with workload and is not prevented by beta-blockade.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The progressive airway dilation with increasing exercise is mediated by a progressive reduction in resting vagal tone.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Beta blockade with propranolol causes a rebound in airway resistance after exercise in normal subjects over the same time course as the bronchoconstriction seen with exercise-induced asthma.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The reduction in airway resistance during exercise reduces the work of breathing.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Every emotional response has a behavioral, an autonomic, and a hormonal component.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The hormonal component includes the release of adrenaline, an adrenomedullary response to stress controlled by the sympathetic nervous system.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The major emotion studied in relation to adrenaline is fear.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] In an experiment, subjects who were injected with adrenaline expressed more negative and fewer positive facial expressions to fear films compared to a control group.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] These subjects also reported a more intense fear from the films and greater mean intensity of negative memories than control subjects.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The findings from this study demonstrate that there are learned associations between negative feelings and levels of adrenaline.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Overall, the greater amount of adrenaline is positively correlated with an aroused state of negative emotions.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] These findings can be an effect in part that adrenaline elicits physiological sympathetic responses, including an increased heart rate and knee shaking, which can be attributed to the feeling of fear regardless of the actual level of fear elicited from the video.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Although studies have found a definite relation between adrenaline and fear, other emotions have not had such results.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] In the same study, subjects did not express a greater amusement to an amusement film nor greater anger to an anger film.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Similar findings were also supported in a study that involved rodent subjects that either were able or unable to produce adrenaline.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Findings support the idea that adrenaline has a role in facilitating the encoding of emotionally arousing events, contributing to higher levels of arousal due to fear.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] It has been found that adrenergic hormones, such as adrenaline, can produce retrograde enhancement of long-term memory in humans.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The release of adrenaline due to emotionally stressful events, which is endogenous adrenaline, can modulate memory consolidation of the events, ensuring memory strength that is proportional to memory importance.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Post-learning adrenaline activity also interacts with the degree of arousal associated with the initial coding.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] There is evidence that suggests adrenaline does have a role in long-term stress adaptation and emotional memory encoding specifically.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenaline may also play a role in elevating arousal and fear memory under particular pathological conditions, including post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Overall, "Extensive evidence indicates that epinephrine (EPI) modulates memory consolidation for emotionally arousing tasks in animals and human subjects." Studies have also found that recognition memory involving adrenaline depends on a mechanism that depends on β adrenoceptors.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenaline does not readily cross the blood-brain barrier, so its effects on memory consolidation are at least partly initiated by β adrenoceptors in the periphery.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Studies have found that sotalol, a β adrenoceptor antagonist that also does not readily enter the brain, blocks the enhancing effects of peripherally administered adrenaline on memory.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] These findings suggest that β adrenoceptors are necessary for adrenaline to have an impact on memory consolidation.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Increased adrenaline secretion is observed in pheochromocytoma, hypoglycemia, myocardial infarction, and to a lesser degree, in essential tremor (also known as benign, familial, or idiopathic tremor).
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] A general increase in sympathetic neural activity is usually accompanied by increased adrenaline secretion, but there is selectivity during hypoxia and hypoglycemia, when the ratio of adrenaline to noradrenaline is considerably increased.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Therefore, there must be some autonomy of the adrenal medulla from the rest of the sympathetic system.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Myocardial infarction is associated with high levels of circulating adrenaline and noradrenaline, particularly in cardiogenic shock.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Benign familial tremor (essential tremor) (BFT) is responsive to peripheral β adrenergic blockers, and β2-stimulation is known to cause tremor.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Patients with BFT were found to have increased plasma adrenaline but not noradrenaline.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Low or absent concentrations of adrenaline can be seen in autonomic neuropathy or following adrenalectomy.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Failure of the adrenal cortex, as with Addison's disease, can suppress adrenaline secretion as the activity of the synthesizing enzyme, phenylethanolamine-*N*-methyltransferase, depends on the high concentration of cortisol that drains from the cortex to the medulla.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] In 1901, Jōkichi Takamine patented a purified extract from the adrenal glands, which was trademarked by Parke, Davis & Co in the US.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The British Approved Name and *European Pharmacopoeia* term for this drug is hence *adrenaline* (from Latin *ad*, "on", and *rēnālis*, "of the kidney", from *ren*, "kidney").
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] However, the pharmacologist John Abel had already prepared an extract from adrenal glands as early as 1897, and he coined the name *epinephrine*to describe it (from Ancient Greek ἐπῐ́ (*epí*), "upon", and νεφρός (*nephrós*), "kidney").
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The terminology is now one of the few differences between the INN and BAN systems of names.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Although European health professionals and scientists preferentially use the term *adrenaline*, the converse is true among American health professionals and scientists.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Nevertheless, even among the latter, receptors for this substance are called *adrenergic receptors* or *adrenoceptors*, and pharmaceuticals that mimic its effects are often called *adrenergics*.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The history of adrenaline and epinephrine is reviewed by Rao.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] As a hormone, adrenaline acts on nearly all body tissues by binding to adrenergic receptors.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Its effects on various tissues depend on the type of tissue and expression of specific forms of adrenergic receptors.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] For example, high levels of adrenaline cause smooth muscle relaxation in the airways but causes contraction of the smooth muscle that lines most arterioles.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenaline is a nonselective agonist of all adrenergic receptors, including the major subtypes α1, α2, β1, β2, and β3.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenaline's binding to these receptors triggers a number of metabolic changes.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Together, these effects increase blood glucose and fatty acids, providing substrates for energy production within cells throughout the body.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Binding of β adrenergic receptor also increases the production of cyclic AMP.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenaline causes liver cells to release glucose into the blood, acting through both alpha and beta-adrenergic receptors to stimulate glycogenolysis.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenaline binds to β2 receptors on liver cells, which changes conformation and helps Gs, a heterotrimeric G protein, exchange GDP to GTP.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] This trimeric G protein dissociates to Gs alpha and Gs beta/gamma subunits.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Gs alpha stimulates adenylyl cyclase, thus converting adenosine triphosphate into cyclic adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Protein kinase A phosphorylates and partially activates phosphorylase kinase.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenaline also binds to α1 adrenergic receptors, causing an increase in inositol trisphosphate, inducing calcium ions to enter the cytoplasm.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Calcium ions bind to calmodulin, which leads to further activation of phosphorylase kinase.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Phosphorylase kinase phosphorylates glycogen phosphorylase, which then breaks down glycogen leading to the production of glucose.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenaline also has significant effects on the cardiovascular system.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] It increases peripheral resistance via α1 receptor-dependent vasoconstriction and increases cardiac output by binding to β1 receptors.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The goal of reducing peripheral circulation is to increase coronary and cerebral perfusion pressures and therefore increase oxygen exchange at the cellular level.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] While adrenaline does increase aortic, cerebral, and carotid circulation pressure, it lowers carotid blood flow and end-tidal CO2 or ETCO2 levels.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] It appears that adrenaline improves microcirculation at the expense of the capillary beds where perfusion takes place.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenaline may be quantified in blood, plasma, or serum as a diagnostic aid, to monitor therapeutic administration, or to identify the causative agent in a potential poisoning victim.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Endogenous plasma adrenaline concentrations in resting adults usually are less than 10 ng/L, but they may increase by 10-fold during exercise and by 50-fold or more during times of stress.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Pheochromocytoma patients often have plasma adrenaline levels of 1000–10,000 ng/L.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Parenteral administration of adrenaline to acute-care cardiac patients can produce plasma concentrations of 10,000 to 100,000 ng/L.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] In chemical terms, adrenaline is one of a group of monoamines called the catecholamines.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Tyrosine is first oxidized to L-DOPA by tyrosine hydroxylase; this is the rate-limiting step.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Then it is subsequently decarboxylated to give dopamine by DOPA decarboxylase (aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase).
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Dopamine is then converted to noradrenaline by dopamine beta-hydroxylase, which utilizes ascorbic acid (vitamin C) and copper.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The final step in adrenaline biosynthesis is the methylation of the primary amine of noradrenaline.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] This reaction is catalyzed by the enzyme phenylethanolamine *N*-methyltransferase (PNMT), which utilizes *S*-adenosyl methionine (SAMe) as the methyl donor.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] While PNMT is found primarily in the cytosol of the endocrine cells of the adrenal medulla (also known as chromaffin cells), it has been detected at low levels in both the heart and brain.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The major physiologic triggers of adrenaline release center upon stresses, such as physical threat, excitement, noise, bright lights, and high or low ambient temperature.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] All of these stimuli are processed in the central nervous system.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) and the sympathetic nervous system stimulate the synthesis of adrenaline precursors by enhancing the activity of tyrosine hydroxylase and dopamine β-hydroxylase, two key enzymes involved in catecholamine synthesis.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] ACTH also stimulates the adrenal cortex to release cortisol, which increases the expression of PNMT in chromaffin cells, enhancing adrenaline synthesis.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] This is most often done in response to stress.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The sympathetic nervous system, acting via splanchnic nerves to the adrenal medulla, stimulates the release of adrenaline.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Acetylcholine released by preganglionic sympathetic fibers of these nerves acts on nicotinic acetylcholine receptors, causing cell depolarization and an influx of calcium through voltage-gated calcium channels.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Calcium triggers the exocytosis of chromaffin granules and, thus, the release of adrenaline (and noradrenaline) into the bloodstream.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] For noradrenaline to be acted upon by PNMT in the cytosol, it must first be shipped out of granules of the chromaffin cells.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] This may occur via the catecholamine-H+ exchanger VMAT1.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] VMAT1 is also responsible for transporting newly synthesized adrenaline from the cytosol back into chromaffin granules in preparation for release.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Unlike many other hormones, adrenaline (as with other catecholamines) does not exert negative feedback to down-regulate its own synthesis.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Abnormal adrenaline levels can occur in various conditions, such as surreptitious adrenaline administration, pheochromocytoma, and other tumors of the sympathetic ganglia.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Its action is terminated with reuptake into nerve terminal endings, some minute dilution, and metabolism by monoamine oxidase and catechol-*O*-methyl transferase into 3,4-Dihydroxymandelic acid and Metanephrine.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenaline, also known as 3,4,β-trihydroxy-*N*-methylphenethylamine, is a substituted phenethylamine and catecholamine.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] It is the *N*-methylated analogue of norepinephrine (noradrenaline; 3,4,β-trihydroxyphenethylamine) and the *N*-methylated and β-hydroxylated analogue of dopamine (3,4-dihydroxyphenethylamine).
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Its chemical composition is Nonacarbon Tridecahydrogen Nitrogen Trioxygen (C9H13NO3).
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Extracts of the adrenal gland were first obtained by Polish physiologist Napoleon Cybulski in 1895.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] These extracts, which he called *nadnerczyna* ("adrenalin"), contained adrenaline and other catecholamines.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Bates discovered adrenaline's usage for eye surgeries prior to 20 April 1896.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] In 1897, John Jacob Abel (1857–1938), the father of modern pharmacology, found a natural substance produced by the adrenal glands that he named epinephrine.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The first hormone to be identified, it remains a crucial, first-line treatment for cardiac arrests, severe allergic reactions, and other conditions.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] In 1901, Jokichi Takamine successfully isolated and purified the hormone from the adrenal glands of sheep and oxen.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenaline was first synthesized in the laboratory by Friedrich Stolz and Henry Drysdale Dakin, independently, in 1904.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Although secretin is mentioned as the first hormone, adrenaline is the first hormone since the discovery of the activity of adrenal extract on blood pressure was observed in 1895 before that of secretin in 1902.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] In 1897, John Jacob Abel (1857–1938) of Johns Hopkins University, the first chairman of the first US department of pharmacology, found a compound called epinephrine with the molecular formula of C17H15NO4.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Abel claimed his principle from adrenal gland extract was active.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] In 1900, Jōkichi Takamine (1854–1922), a Japanese chemist, worked with his assistant, Keizo Uenaka (1876–1960), to purify a 2000 times more active principle than epinephrine from the adrenal gland, named adrenaline with the molecular formula C10H15NO3.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Additionally, in 1900 Thomas Aldrich of Parke-Davis Scientific Laboratory also purified adrenaline independently.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Takamine and Parke-Davis later in 1901 both got the patent for adrenaline.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The fight for terminology between adrenaline and epinephrine was not ended until the first adrenaline structural discovery by Hermann Pauly (1870–1950) in 1903 and the first adrenaline synthesis by Friedrich Stolz (1860–1936), a German chemist in 1904.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] They both believed that Takamine's compound was the active principle while Abel's compound was the inactive one.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Stolz synthesized adrenaline from its ketone form (adrenalone).
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] An *adrenaline junkie* is someone who "has a compulsive desire for extreme excitement".
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Such activities include extreme and risky sports, substance abuse, unsafe sex, and crime.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] The term relates to the increase in circulating levels of adrenaline during physiological stress.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Such an increase in the circulating concentration of adrenaline is secondary to the activation of the sympathetic nerves innervating the adrenal medulla, as it is rapid and not present in animals where the adrenal gland has been removed.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Although such stress triggers adrenaline release, it also activates many other responses within the central nervous system reward system, which drives behavioral responses; while the circulating adrenaline concentration is present, it may not drive behavior.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Nevertheless, adrenaline infusion alone does increase alertness and has roles in the brain, including the augmentation of memory consolidation.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] Adrenaline has been implicated in feats of great strength, often occurring in times of crisis.
[src:home-sports/adrenaline] For example, there are stories of a parent lifting part of a car when their child is trapped underneath, showcasing the ability of the body to endure under stress and highlighting the significant effects of adrenaline in unlocking extraordinary physical abilities.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] American football evolved in the United States, originating from the sports of soccer and rugby.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between two college teams, Rutgers and Princeton, using rules based on the rules of soccer at the time; by 1875, the sport had adopted rules similar to rugby union.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A set of rule changes drawn up from 1880 onward by Walter Camp, the "Father of American Football", established concepts that would define the sport, among them the snap, the line of scrimmage, eleven-player teams, and the concept of downs.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Later rule changes legalized the forward pass, created the neutral zone, and specified the size and shape of the football.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The modern sport is closely related to Canadian football, which evolved in parallel with and at the same time as the American game; the two sports are considered the primary variants of gridiron football.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] American football is the most popular sport in the United States; the most popular forms of the game are professional and college football, with the other major levels being high school and youth football.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Over a million Americans played college or high school football in 2022, and the National Football League (NFL) has one of the highest average attendance of any professional sports league in the world.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Its championship game, the Super Bowl, ranks among the most-watched club sporting events globally.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Other professional and amateur leagues exist worldwide, but the sport does not have the international popularity of other American sports like baseball or basketball; the sport maintains a growing following in the rest of North America, Europe, Brazil, and Japan.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Flag football, a variant of the sport, will be played at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In the United States, American football is referred to as "football".
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The term "football" was officially established in the rulebook for the 1876 college football season, when the sport first shifted from soccer-style rules to rugby-style rules.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Although it could easily have been called "rugby" at this point, Harvard, one of the primary proponents of the rugby-style game, compromised and did not request the name of the sport be changed to "rugby".
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The terms "gridiron" or "American football" are favored in English-speaking countries where other types of football are popular, such as the United Kingdom, Ireland, New Zealand, and Australia.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] American football evolved from the sports of rugby and soccer.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Rugby, like American football, is a sport in which two competing teams vie for control of a ball, which can be kicked through a set of goalposts or run into the opponent's goal area to score points.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] What is considered to be the first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between Rutgers and Princeton, two college teams.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] They consisted of 25 players per team and used a round ball that could not be picked up or carried.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] It could, however, be kicked or batted with the feet, hands, head, or sides, with the objective being to advance it into the opponent's goal.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Collegiate play continued for several years with games played using the rules of the host school.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Representatives of Yale, Columbia, Princeton and Rutgers met on October 19, 1873, to create a standard set of rules for use by all schools.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Teams were set at 20 players each, and fields of 400 by 250 feet (122 m × 76 m) were specified.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Harvard abstained from the conference, as they favored a rugby-style game that allowed running with the ball.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] An 1875 Harvard–Yale game played under rugby-style rules was observed by two Princeton athletes who were impressed by it.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] They introduced the sport to Princeton, a feat the Professional Football Researchers Association compared to "selling refrigerators to Eskimos".
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Princeton, Harvard, Yale, and Columbia then agreed to intercollegiate play using a form of rugby union rules with a modified scoring system.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] These schools formed the Intercollegiate Football Association, although Yale did not join until 1879.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Yale player Walter Camp, now regarded as the "Father of American Football", secured rule changes in 1880 that reduced the size of each team from 15 to 11 players and instituted the snap to replace the chaotic and inconsistent scrum.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] While the game between Rutgers and Princeton is commonly considered the first American football game, several years prior in 1862, the Oneida Football Club formed as the oldest known football club in the United States.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The team consisted of graduates of Boston's elite preparatory schools and played from 1862 to 1865.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The introduction of the snap resulted in an unexpected consequence.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Before the snap, the strategy had been to punt if a scrum resulted in a bad field position.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] However, a group of Princeton players realized that, as the snap was uncontested, they could now hold the ball indefinitely to prevent their opponent from scoring.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In 1881, in a game between Yale and Princeton, both teams used this strategy to maintain their undefeated records.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Each team held the ball, gaining no ground, for an entire half, resulting in a 0–0 tie.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] This "block game" proved extremely unpopular with both teams' spectators and fans.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A rule change was necessary to prevent this strategy from taking hold, and a reversion to the scrum was considered.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] However, Camp successfully proposed a rule in 1882 that limited each team to three downs, or tackles, to advance the ball 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Failure to advance the ball the required distance within those three downs would result in control of the ball being forfeited to the other team.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] This change effectively made American football a separate sport from rugby, and the resulting five-yard lines added to the field to measure distances made it resemble a gridiron in appearance.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Other major rule changes included a reduction of the field size to 110 by 53+1⁄3 yards (100.6 m × 48.8 m) and the adoption of a scoring system that awarded four points for a touchdown, two for a safety and a goal following a touchdown, and five for a goal from the field.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Additionally, tackling below the waist was legalized, and a static line of scrimmage was instituted.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Despite these new rules, football remained a violent sport.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Dangerous mass-formations like the flying wedge resulted in serious injuries and deaths.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A 1905 peak of 19 fatalities nationwide resulted in a threat by President Theodore Roosevelt to abolish the game unless major changes were made.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In response, 62 colleges and universities met in New York City to discuss rule changes on December 28, 1905.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] These proceedings resulted in the formation of the Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the United States, later renamed the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The legal forward pass was introduced in 1906, although its effect was initially minimal due to the restrictions placed on its use.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The idea of a 40-yard-wider field was opposed by Harvard due to the size of the new Harvard Stadium.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Other rule changes introduced that year included the reduction of playing time from 70 to 60 minutes and an increase of the distance required for a first down from 5 to 10 yards (4.6 to 9.1 m).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] To reduce infighting and dirty play between teams, the neutral zone was created along the width of the football before the snap.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Scoring was also adjusted: points awarded for field goals were reduced to three in 1909 and points for touchdowns were raised to six in 1912.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Also in 1912, the field was shortened to 100 yards (91 m) long, two 10-yard-long (9.1 m) end zones were created, and teams were given four downs instead of three to advance the ball 10 yards (9.1 m).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The roughing the passer penalty was implemented in 1914, and eligible players were first allowed to catch the ball anywhere on the field in 1918.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] On November 12, 1892, Pudge Heffelfinger was paid $500 (equivalent to $17,917 in 2025) to play a game for the Allegheny Athletic Association against the Pittsburgh Athletic Club.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Despite these extra benefits, the game had a strict sense of amateurism at the time, and direct payment to players was frowned upon, if not prohibited outright.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Over time, professional play became increasingly common, and with it came rising salaries and unpredictable player movement, as well as the illegal payment of college players who were still in school.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The National Football League (NFL), a group of professional teams that was originally established in 1920 as the American Professional Football Association, aimed to solve these problems.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] This new league's stated goals included an end to bidding wars over players, prevention of the use of college players, and abolition of the practice of paying players to leave another team.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] By 1922, the NFL had established itself as America's premier professional football league.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The dominant form of football at the time was played at the collegiate level.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The upstart NFL received a boost to its legitimacy in 1925, however, when an NFL team, the Pottsville Maroons, defeated a team of Notre Dame all-stars in an exhibition game.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A greater emphasis on the passing game helped professional football to distinguish itself further from the college game during the late 1930s.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Football, in general, became increasingly popular following the 1958 NFL Championship game between the Baltimore Colts and the New York Giants, still referred to as the "Greatest Game Ever Played".
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The game, a 23–17 overtime victory by the Colts, was seen by millions of television viewers and had a major influence on the popularity of the sport.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] By the mid-1960s, football was the most popular sport in the United States.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In 1972, polling from Gallup, Inc. found that twice as many Americans identified football as their favorite sport (38%) as compared to baseball (19%); the sport has remained the most popular in the United States since.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In 1960, the American Football League (AFL) was created to compete with the NFL.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The AFL began in relative obscurity but eventually thrived, with an initial television contract with the ABC television network.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The AFL's existence forced the conservative NFL to expand to Dallas and Minnesota in an attempt to destroy the new league.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Meanwhile, the AFL introduced many new features to professional football in the United States and actively recruited minority players.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The AFL also signed several star college players who had also been drafted by NFL teams.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Competition for players heated up in 1965, when the AFL New York Jets signed rookie Joe Namath to a then-record $437,000 contract (equivalent to $4.46 million in 2024).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A five-year, $40 million NBC television contract followed, which helped to sustain the young league.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The bidding war for players ended in 1966 when NFL owners approached the AFL regarding a merger, and the two leagues agreed on one that took full effect in 1970.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] This agreement provided for a common draft that would take place each year, and it instituted an annual World Championship game to be played between the champions of each league.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] This championship game, which would come to be known as the Super Bowl, began play at the end of the 1966 season.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Once the merger was completed, it was no longer a championship game between two leagues, instead being competed between the American Football Conference (AFC) and the National Football Conference (NFC).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Prior to the 1956 college football season, NCAA schools were organized into an upper University Division and lower College Division.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In the summer of 1973, the University Division became Division I, but by 1976, there was a desire to further separate the major football programs from those that were less financially successful, while still allowing their other sports to compete at the top level.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In 1978, the NCAA divided Division I football into two subdivisions: NCAA Division I-A (known today as the Football Bowl Subdivision, or FBS) and Division I-AA (known today as the Football Championship Subdivision, or FCS).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The FCS adopted a single-elimination playoff structure to determine its champion, while the FBS retained its tradition of postseason bowl games.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Each bowl game was associated with a particular conference, and earning a spot in a major bowl game was the reward for winning a conference.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] This arrangement was beneficial to both conferences and bowl games, but it generally prevented the top-ranked teams from meeting in a true national championship game.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Because the NCAA itself does not officially sanction a Division I-FBS national champion, FBS national champions prior to 1992 were determined by polls, which frequently led to controversial or "split" national champions.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In 1992, the Bowl Coalition was created to determine the national champion.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] It was replaced in 1995 by the Bowl Alliance, which itself gave way to the Bowl Championship Series (BCS) in 1997.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] All three of these systems consisted of a single national championship game, as well as a set of other major bowl games.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In 2014, the BCS was replaced by the College Football Playoff (CFP), a single-elimination tournament.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In another major change, in 2021, following legal pressure and antitrust lawsuits, the NCAA and its conferences began allowing schools to offer compensation to student athletes for the use of their names, images, and likenesses (NIL).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] NCAA* allowed schools to directly pay players, ending the traditionally amateur nature of college athletics in the United States.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A football game is played between two teams of 11 players each.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Playing with more on the field is punishable by a penalty.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Teams may substitute any number of their players between downs; this "platoon" system has resulted in teams utilizing specialized offensive, defensive and special teams units.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The number of players allowed on an active roster varies by league; the NFL has a 53-man roster, while NCAA Division I allows teams to have up to 105 players on their roster.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Individual players in a football game must be designated with a uniform number between 0 and 99.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] NFL teams are required to number their players by a league-approved numbering system, and any exceptions must be approved by the commissioner.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] NCAA and NFHS teams are "strongly advised" to number their offensive players according to a league-suggested numbering scheme.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Women are eligible to play in high school, college, and professional football, but most football players are men.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] No woman has ever played in the NFL, but women have played in high school and college football games.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In 2018, women and girls comprised 0.5% of players in Pop Warner Little Scholars youth football, 0.2% of players in high school football, and 10.9% of Americans who report playing tackle football.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The role of the offensive unit is to advance the football down the field with the ultimate goal of scoring a touchdown.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The offensive team must line up in a legal formation before they can snap the ball.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] An offensive formation is considered illegal if there are more than four players in the backfield or fewer than five players numbered 50–79 on the offensive line.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Players can line up temporarily in a position whose eligibility is different from what their number permits as long as they report the change immediately to the referee, who then informs the defensive team of the change.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Neither team's players, except the center (C), are allowed to line up in or cross the neutral zone until the ball is snapped.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Interior offensive linemen are not allowed to move until the snap of the ball.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The main backfield positions are the quarterback (QB), running back (RB), and fullback (FB).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The quarterback is the leader of the offense.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Either the quarterback or a coach calls the plays.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Quarterbacks typically inform the rest of the offense of the play in the huddle before the team lines up.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The quarterback lines up behind the center to take the snap and then hands the ball off, throws it, or runs with it.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The primary role of the running back is to carry the ball on running plays.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Fullbacks tend to be larger than halfbacks and function primarily as blockers, but they are sometimes used as runners in short-yardage or goal-line situations.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The offensive line (OL) consists of several players whose primary function is to block members of the defensive line from tackling the ball carrier on running plays or sacking the quarterback on passing plays.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The most important role on the offensive line is the center, who is not just responsible for blocking and snapping the ball, but also for handling line adjustments and pre-snap strategy.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] On either side of the center are the guards (G), while tackles (T) line up outside the guards.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The principal receivers are the wide receivers (WR) and the tight ends (TE).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Wide receivers line up on or near the line of scrimmage, split outside the line.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The main goal of the wide receiver is to catch passes thrown by the quarterback, but they may also function as decoys or as blockers during running plays.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Tight ends line up next to the offensive line and function both as receivers and as blockers.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The role of the defense is to prevent the offense from scoring by tackling the ball carrier or by forcing turnovers.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Turnovers include interceptions (a defender catching a forward pass intended for the offense) and forced fumbles (taking possession of the ball from the ball-carrier).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The defensive line (DL) consists of defensive ends (DE) and defensive tackles (DT).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Defensive ends line up on the ends of the defensive line, while defensive tackles line up on the inside, between the defensive ends.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The primary responsibilities of defensive ends and defensive tackles are to stop running plays on the outside and inside, respectively, to pressure the quarterback on passing plays, and to occupy the line so that the linebackers can break through.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Linebackers line up behind the defensive line but in front of the defensive backfield.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] They are divided into two types: middle linebackers (MLB) and outside linebackers (OLB).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Linebackers tend to serve as the defensive leaders and call the defensive plays, given their vantage point of the offensive backfield.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Their roles include defending the run, pressuring the quarterback, and tackling backs, wide receivers, and tight ends.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The defensive backfield, often called the secondary, consists of cornerbacks (CB) and safeties (S).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties are themselves divided into free safeties (FS) and strong safeties (SS).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Cornerbacks line up outside the defensive formation, typically opposite a receiver to be able to cover them.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties line up between the cornerbacks but farther back in the secondary.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties tend to be viewed as "the last line of defense" and are responsible for stopping deep passing plays as well as breakout running plays.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The special teams unit is responsible for all kicking plays.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The special teams unit of the team in control of the ball tries to execute field goal (FG) attempts, punts, and kickoffs, while the opposing team's unit will aim to block or return them.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Three positions are specific to the field goal and PAT (point after touchdown) unit: the placekicker (K or PK), holder (H), and long snapper (LS).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The long snapper's job is to snap the football to the holder, who will catch and place it on the ground for the kicker.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] There is usually never a holder on kickoffs, because the ball is kicked off a tee; however, a holder may be used in certain situations, such as if wind is preventing the ball from remaining upright on the tee.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The player on the receiving team who catches the ball is known as the kick returner (KR).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The positions specific to punt plays are the punter (P), long snapper, upback, and gunner.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The long snapper snaps the football directly to the punter, who then drops and kicks it before it hits the ground.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Gunners line up split outside the line and race down the field, aiming to tackle the punt returner (PR)—the player who catches the punt.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Upbacks line up a short distance, typically 1-7 yards, behind the line of scrimmage, providing additional protection to the punter.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In football, the winner is the team that has scored more points at the end of the game.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] There are multiple ways to score in a football game.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The touchdown (TD), worth six points, is the most valuable scoring play.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A touchdown is scored when a live ball is advanced into, caught, or recovered in the opposing team's end zone.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The scoring team then attempts a try, more commonly known as the point(s)-after-touchdown (PAT) or conversion, which is a single scoring opportunity.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by a place kick or drop kick through the goal posts, it is worth one point, typically called the extra point.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by what would normally be a touchdown, it is worth two points; this is known as a two-point conversion.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In general, the extra point is almost always successful, while the two-point conversion is a much riskier play with a higher probability of failure; accordingly, extra point attempts are far more common than two-point conversion attempts.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A field goal (FG), worth three points, is scored when the ball is place kicked or drop kicked through the uprights and over the crossbars of the defense's goalposts.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Almost all field goal attempts are done via place kick.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] While drop kicks were common in the early days of the sport, the shape of modern footballs makes it difficult to reliably drop kick the ball.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The last successful scoring play by drop kick in the NFL was accomplished in 2006; prior to that, the last successful drop kick had been made in 1941.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] After a PAT attempt or successful field goal, the scoring team must kick the ball off to the other team.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A safety is scored when the ball carrier is tackled in the carrier's own end zone.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties are worth two points, which are awarded to the defense.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In addition, the team that conceded the safety must kick the ball to the scoring team via a free kick.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Safeties are the least common method of scoring in football.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Football games are played on a rectangular field that measures 120 yards (110 m) long and 53+1⁄3 yards (48.8 m) wide.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Lines marked along the ends and sides of the field are known as the end lines and sidelines.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Goal lines are marked 10 yards (9.1 m) inward from each end line.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Weighted pylons are placed along each sideline, on the inside corner of the intersections with the goal lines and end lines.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] White markings on the field identify the distance from the end zone.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Inbound lines, or hash marks, are short parallel lines that mark off 1-yard (0.91 m) increments.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Yard lines, which can run the width of the field, are marked every 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A one-yard-wide line is placed at each end of the field; this line is marked at the center of the two-yard line in professional play and at the three-yard line in college play.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Numerals that display the distance from the closest goal line in yards are placed on both sides of the field every ten yards.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Goalposts are located at the center of the plane of the two end lines.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The crossbar of these posts is 10 feet (3.0 m) above the ground, with vertical uprights at the end of the crossbar 18 feet 6 inches (5.64 m) apart for professional and collegiate play, and 23 feet 4 inches (7.11 m) apart for high school play.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The uprights extend vertically 35 feet (11 m) on professional fields, a minimum of 10 yards (9.1 m) on college fields, and a minimum of 10 feet (3.0 m) on high school fields.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Goal posts are padded at the base, and orange ribbons are normally placed at the tip of each upright as indicators of wind strength and direction.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The football itself is a prolate spheroid leather ball, similar to the balls used in rugby or Australian rules football.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] At all levels of play, the football is inflated to 12+1⁄2 to 13+1⁄2 psi (86 to 93 kPa), or just under one atmosphere, and weighs 14 to 15 ounces (400 to 430 g); beyond that, the exact dimensions vary slightly.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In professional play the ball has a long axis of 11 to 11+1⁄4 inches (28 to 29 cm), a long circumference of 28 to 28+1⁄2 inches (71 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 21 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In college and high school play the ball has a long axis of 10+7⁄8 to 11+7⁄16 inches (27.6 to 29.1 cm), a long circumference of 27+3⁄4 to 28+1⁄2 inches (70 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 20+3⁄4 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Football games last for a total of 60 minutes in professional and college play and are divided into two halves of 30 minutes and four quarters of 15 minutes.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] High school football games are 48 minutes in length with two halves of 24 minutes and four quarters of 12 minutes.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The two halves are separated by a halftime period, and the first and third quarters are followed by a short break.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Before the game starts, the referee and each team's captain meet at midfield for a coin toss.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The visiting team can call either "heads" or "tails"; the winner of the toss chooses whether to receive or kick off the ball or which goal they wish to defend.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] They can defer their choice until the second half.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Unless the winning team decides to defer, the losing team chooses the option the winning team did not select—to receive, kick, or select a goal to defend to begin the second half.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Most teams choose to receive or defer, because choosing to kick the ball to start the game allows the other team to choose which goal to defend.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Teams switch goals following the first and third quarters.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] If a down is in progress when a quarter ends, play continues until the down is completed.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] If certain fouls are committed during play while time has expired, the quarter may be extended through an untimed down.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Games last longer than their defined length due to play stoppages—the average NFL game lasts slightly over three hours.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Time in a football game is measured by the game clock.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] An operator is responsible for starting, stopping and operating the game clock based on the direction of the appropriate official.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A separate play clock is used to show the amount of time within which the offense must initiate a play.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The play clock is set to 25 seconds after certain administrative stoppages in play and to 40 seconds when play is proceeding without such stoppages.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] If the offense fails to start a play before the play clock reads "00", a delay of game foul is called on the offense.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] There are two main ways the offense can advance the ball: running and passing.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In a typical play, the center passes the ball backwards and between their legs to the quarterback in a process known as the snap.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The quarterback then either hands the ball off to a running back, throws the ball, or runs with it.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The play ends when the player with the ball is tackled or goes out-of-bounds or a pass hits the ground without a player having caught it.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A forward pass can be legally attempted only if the passer is behind the line of scrimmage; only one forward pass can be attempted per down.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] As in rugby, players can also pass the ball backwards at any point during a play.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In the NFL, a down also ends immediately if the runner's helmet comes off.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The offense is given a series of four plays, known as downs.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] If the offense advances ten or more yards in the four downs, they are awarded a new set of four downs.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] If they fail to advance ten yards, possession of the football is turned over to the defense.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] In most situations, if the offense reaches their fourth down they will punt the ball to the other team, which forces them to begin their drive from farther down the field; if they are in field goal range, they might attempt to score a field goal instead.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A group of officials, the chain crew, keeps track of both the downs and the distance measurements.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The spot needed to secure a first down is known as the line to gain.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] On television, a yellow line is electronically superimposed on the field to show the line to gain to the viewing audience.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] There are two categories of kicks in football: scrimmage kicks, which can be executed by the offensive team on any down from behind or on the line of scrimmage, and free kicks.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The free kicks are the kickoff, which starts the first and third quarters and overtime and follows a try attempt or a successful field goal, and the safety kick, which follows a safety.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] On a kickoff, the ball is placed at the 35-yard line of the kicking team in professional and college play and at the 40-yard line in high school play.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The ball may be drop kicked or place kicked.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] If a place kick is chosen, the ball can be placed on the ground or a tee; a holder may be used in either case.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] On a safety kick, the kicking team kicks the ball from their own 20-yard line.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] They can punt, drop kick or place kick the ball, but a tee may not be used in professional play.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Any member of the receiving team may catch or advance the ball.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The ball may be recovered by the kicking team once it has gone at least ten yards and has touched the ground or has been touched by any member of the receiving team.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The three types of scrimmage kicks are place kicks, drop kicks, and punts.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Only place kicks and drop kicks can score points.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The place kick is the standard method used to score points, because the pointy shape of the football makes it difficult to reliably drop kick.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Once the ball has been kicked from a scrimmage kick, it can be advanced by the kicking team only if it is caught or recovered behind the line of scrimmage.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] If it is touched or recovered by the kicking team beyond this line, it becomes dead at the spot where it was touched.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The kicking team is prohibited from interfering with the receiver's opportunity to catch the ball.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The receiving team has the option of signaling for a fair catch, which prohibits the defense from blocking into or tackling the receiver.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The play ends as soon as the ball is caught, and the ball may not be advanced.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Officials are responsible for enforcing game rules and monitoring the clock.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] All officials carry a whistle and wear black-and-white striped shirts and black hats, except for the referee, whose hat is white.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Each carries a weighted yellow flag that is thrown to the ground to signal that a foul has been called.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] An official who spots multiple fouls will throw their hat as a secondary signal.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Women can serve as officials; Sarah Thomas became the NFL's first female official in 2015.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Another set of officials, the chain crew, are responsible for moving the chains.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The chains, consisting of two large sticks with a 10-yard-long chain between them, are used to measure for a first down.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The chain crew stays on the sidelines during the game, but if requested by the officials, they will briefly bring the chains onto the field to measure.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A typical chain crew will have at least three people—two members of the chain crew will hold either of the two sticks, while a third will hold the down marker.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The down marker, a large stick with a dial on it, is flipped after each play to indicate the current down and is typically moved to the approximate spot of the ball.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The chain crew system has been used for over 100 years and is considered an accurate measure of distance, rarely subject to criticism from either side.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Football is a full-contact sport, and injuries are relatively common.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur during training sessions, particularly ones that involve contact between players.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] To try to prevent injuries, players are required to wear a set of equipment.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] At a minimum players must wear a football helmet and a set of shoulder pads, but individual leagues may require additional padding such as thigh pads and guards, knee pads, chest protectors, and mouthguards.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur in the lower extremities, particularly in the knee, but a significant number also affect the upper extremities.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] The most common types of injuries are strains, sprains, bruises, fractures, dislocations, and concussions.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Repeated concussions (and possibly sub-concussive head impacts) can increase a person's risk in later life for CTE (chronic traumatic encephalopathy) and health issues such as dementia, Parkinson's disease, and depression.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Concussions are often caused by helmet-to-helmet or upper-body contact between opposing players, although helmets have prevented more serious injuries such as skull fractures.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] However, a study in the *Orthopaedic Journal of Sports Medicine* found that Heads Up Football was ineffective; the same study noted that more extensive reforms implemented by Pop Warner Little Scholars and its member teams were effective in significantly reducing concussion rates.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] A 2018 study performed by the VA Boston Healthcare System and the Boston University School of Medicine found that tackle football before age 12 was correlated with earlier onset of symptoms of CTE, but not with increased symptom severity.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] More specifically, each year a player played tackle football under age 12 predicted earlier onset of cognitive, behavioral, and mood problems by an average of two and a half years.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] To help mitigate injuries, the NCAA recommends limiting full contact (tackling to the ground) practices, avoiding full contact on consecutive days, and no more than 20 hours of practice per week.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p01] Players must receive one day off per week.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The National Football League (NFL) and the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) are the most popular football leagues in the United States.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The National Football League was founded in 1920 and has since become the largest and most popular sport in the United States.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL has the highest average attendance of any sporting league in the world, with an average attendance of 66,960 during the 2011 NFL season.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL championship game is called the Super Bowl, and is among the biggest events in club sports worldwide.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] It is played between the champions of the National Football Conference (NFC) and the American Football Conference (AFC), and its winner is awarded the Vince Lombardi Trophy.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] College football is the third-most popular sport in the United States, behind professional football and professional baseball, respectively.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The NCAA, the largest collegiate organization, is divided into three Divisions: Division I, Division II and Division III.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Division I is the highest level of play, while Division III is the lowest; Division I and II programs can offer athletic scholarships to student-athletes, while Division III programs cannot.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Division I football is further divided into two subdivisions: the Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS) and the Football Championship Subdivision (FCS).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The champions of each level of play are determined through playoff systems.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Other national college football organizations include the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA), which comprises around 90 smaller colleges, and the National Junior College Athletic Association (NJCAA), whose membership consists of two-year colleges.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] High school football is the most popular sport in the United States played by boys.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The NFHS is the largest organization for high school football, with member associations in all 50 states as well as the District of Columbia.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] USA Football is the governing body for youth and amateur football, and Pop Warner Little Scholars is the largest organization for youth football.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The most successful league to directly compete with the NFL was the American Football League (AFL), which existed from 1960 to 1969.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The AFL became a significant rival in 1964 before signing a five-year, US$36 million television deal with NBC.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] AFL teams began signing NFL players to contracts, and the league's popularity grew to challenge that of the NFL.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged in the 1970 season, and all the AFL teams joined the NFL.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] An earlier league, the All-America Football Conference (AAFC), was in play from 1946 to 1949.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] After it had dissolved, two AAFC teams, the Cleveland Browns and the San Francisco 49ers, became members of the NFL; another member, the Baltimore Colts joined the league, but folded after just a year in the NFL.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Other attempts to start rival leagues since the AFL merged with the NFL in 1970 have been far less successful, as professional football salaries and the NFL's television contracts began to escalate out of the reach of competitors and the NFL covered more of the larger cities.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The World Football League (WFL) played for two seasons, in 1974 and 1975, but faced such severe monetary issues it could not pay its players.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] In its second and final season the WFL attempted to establish a stable credit rating, but the league disbanded before the season could be completed.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The United States Football League (USFL) operated for three seasons from 1983 to 1985.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Originally not intended as a rival league, the entry of owners who sought marquee talent and to challenge the NFL led to an escalation in salaries and ensuing financial losses.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] A subsequent US$1.5 billion antitrust lawsuit against the NFL was successful in court, but the league was awarded only $1 in damages, which was automatically tripled to $3 under antitrust law.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The original XFL, created in 2001 by WWE co-founder Vince McMahon, lasted for only one season.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Despite television contracts with NBC and UPN, and high expectations, the XFL suffered from low quality of play and poor reception for its use of tawdry professional wrestling gimmicks, which caused initially high ratings and attendance to collapse.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The United Football League (UFL) began in 2009 but folded after suspending its 2012 season after having lost $120 million over just three seasons.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Another spring league, the Alliance of American Football lasted less than one season, unable to keep investors.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] A revived United States Football League began play in 2022 and quickly faced immediate competition from the XFL, which resumed play in 2023.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged following the 2023 season, forming a new United Football League (UFL).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] American football leagues exist throughout the world, but the game has yet to achieve the international success and popularity of baseball and basketball.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] At the international level, Canada, Mexico, and Japan are considered to be second-tier, while Austria, Germany, and France would rank among a third tier.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] These countries rank far below the United States, which is dominant at the international level.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] NFL Europa, the developmental league of the NFL, operated from 1991 to 1992 and then from 1995 to 2007.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] At the time of its closure, NFL Europa had five teams based in Germany and one in the Netherlands.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] In Germany, the German Football League (GFL) has 16 teams and has operated for over 40 seasons, with the league's championship game, the German Bowl, closing out each season.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The league operates in a promotion and relegation structure with German Football League 2 (GFL2), which also has 16 teams.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The United Kingdom also operated several teams within NFL Europe during the League's tenure.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The resulting rise in popularity of the sport brought the NFL back to the country in 2007 where they now hold the NFL International Series in London, currently consisting of four regular season games.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The continuing interest and growth in both the sport and the series has led to the possible formation of a potential NFL franchise in London.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] NFL commissioner Roger Goodell aims to host 16 international games each year, enough for each NFL team to play one international game each year.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom, the British American Football Association National Leagues (BAFANL), an amateur competition, is the top level of American football.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Teams compete across multiple levels in a promotion and relegation structure; the league's championship is the Britbowl.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] University competition is held through the British Universities American Football League (BUAFL), which was formed in 2007.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] In 2008, the league launched a partnership with the NFL, through its partner organization NFL UK.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] From 2007 to 2014, the BUAFL grew from 42 teams and 2,460 participants to 75 teams and over 4,100 people involved.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The standard form of American football is not an Olympic sport, but it was a demonstration sport at the 1932 Summer Olympics.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The International Federation of American Football (IFAF), an international governing body composed of continental federations, received provisional recognition from the International Olympic Committee (IOC) in 2014 and was fully recognized by the IOC in 2015.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] American football federations are present in Africa, the Americas, Asia, Europe, and Oceania; a total of 75 national football federations exist as of 2023.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The IFAF runs tournaments such as the IFAF World Championship, the IFAF Women's World Championship, the IFAF Junior World Championship, and the Flag Football World Championship.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Obstacles towards the goal of becoming an Olympic sport included the predominant participation of men in international play and the short three-week Olympic schedule.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Large team sizes were an additional difficulty, due to the Olympics' set limit of 10,500 athletes and coaches.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] American football also faced an issue with a lack of global visibility.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Nigel Melville, the CEO of USA Rugby, noted that "American football is recognized globally as a sport, but it's not played globally." To solve these concerns, major effort was put into promoting flag football, a modified version of American football, at the international level.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Flag football for men and women will debut as an Olympic sport at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] "Baseball is still called the national pastime, but football is by far the more popular sport in American society", according to ESPN.com's Sean McAdam.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] In a 2014 poll conducted by Harris Interactive, professional football ranked as the most popular sport, and college football ranked third behind only professional football and baseball; 46% of participants ranked some form of the game as their favorite sport.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Professional football has ranked as the most popular sport in the poll since 1985, when it surpassed baseball for the first time.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Professional football is most popular among those who live in the eastern United States and rural areas, while college football is most popular in the southern United States and among people with graduate and post-graduate degrees.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Football is also the most-played sport by high school and college athletes in the United States.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] A 2022 survey from National Football Foundation found that one million high-school athletes played the sport, with another 81,000 college athletes across both the NCAA and the NAIA.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The Super Bowl is the most popular single-day sporting event in the United States, and is among the biggest club sporting events in the world in terms of TV viewership.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL made approximately $12 billion in revenue in 2022.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Super Bowl games account for eight of the top ten most-watched broadcasts in American history; Super Bowl LVII, played on February 12, 2023, was watched by a record 115.1 million Americans, and is second only to the Apollo 11 moon landing (125 million viewers).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL is the most valuable sports league in the world, with the average team valued at over $8 billion.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] American football also plays a significant role in American culture.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The day on which the Super Bowl is held is considered a *de facto* national holiday, and in parts of the country like Texas, the sport has been compared to a religion.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Football is also linked to other holidays; New Year's Day is traditionally the date for several college football bowl games, including the Rose Bowl.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] However, if New Year's Day is on a Sunday, the bowl games are moved to another date so as not to conflict with the typical NFL Sunday schedule.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Thanksgiving football is another American tradition, hosting many high school, college, and professional games.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Implicit rules such as playing through pain and sacrificing for the better of the team are promoted in football culture.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] In Canada, the game has a significant following.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] According to a 2013 poll, 21% of respondents said they followed the NFL "very closely" or "fairly closely", making it the third-most followed league behind the National Hockey League (NHL) and Canadian Football League (CFL).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] American football also has a long history in Mexico, which was introduced to the sport in 1896.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] It was the second-most popular sport in Mexico in the 1950s, with the game being particularly popular in colleges.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The *Los Angeles Times* notes the NFL claims over 16 million fans in Mexico, which places the country third behind the U.S. and Canada.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] American football is played in Mexico both professionally and as part of the college sports system.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] A professional league, the Liga de Fútbol Americano Profesional (LFA), was founded in 2016.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Japan was introduced to the sport in 1934 by Paul Rusch, a teacher and Christian missionary who helped to establish football teams at three universities in Tokyo.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Play was halted during World War II by order of Emperor Hirohito, but the sport began growing in popularity again after the war.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] As of 2010, there are more than 400 high school football teams in Japan, with over 15,000 participants, and over 100 teams play in the Kantoh Collegiate Football Association (KCFA).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The X-League is the largest American football league in Japan, and the largest American football league in the world to use a promotion-relegation system.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Some teams in the X-League, like the Panasonic Impulse, are sponsored by corporations, and all Japanese players on these teams are employed by the corporation.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The league operates in separate spring and fall seasons, with each team playing five games.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The top eight teams make the playoffs, which are played in Tokyo Dome; the champion is determined by the Rice Bowl.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Europe is a major target for the expansion of the game by football organizers.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom in the 1980s, the sport was popular, with the 1986 Super Bowl being watched by over four million people (about 1 out of every 14 Britons).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Its popularity faded during the 1990s, coinciding with the establishment of the Premier League—the top level of the English association football (soccer) league system.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] According to BBC America, there is a "social stigma" surrounding American football in the UK, with many Brits feeling the sport has no right to call itself "football" due to the lack of emphasis on kicking.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Nonetheless, the sport has retained a following in the United Kingdom; the NFL operates a media network in the country, and since 2007 has hosted the NFL International Series in London.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Super Bowl viewership has also rebounded, with over 4.4 million Britons watching Super Bowl XLVI.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The sport is played in European countries like Switzerland, which has American football clubs in every major city, and Germany, where the sport has around 45,000 registered amateur players.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] It was generally unknown there until the 1980s when a small group of players began playing on Copacabana Beach in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The sport grew gradually with 700 amateur players registering within 20 years.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Games were played on the beach with modified rules and without the traditional football equipment due to its lack of availability in Brazil.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Eventually, a tournament, the Carioca championship, was founded, with the championship Carioca Bowl played to determine a league champion.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The country saw its first full-pad game of football in October 2008.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] According to *The Rio Times*, the sport is one of the fastest-growing sports in Brazil and is almost as commonly played as soccer on the beaches of Copacabana and Botafogo.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Football in Brazil is governed by the Confederação Brasileira de Futebol Americano (CBFA), which had over 5,000 registered players as of November 2013.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The sport's increase in popularity has been attributed to games aired on ESPN, which began airing in Brazil in 1992 with Portuguese commentary.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The popularity and "easy accessibility" of non-contact versions of the sport in Brazil has led to a rise in participation by female players.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] According to ESPN, the American football audience in Brazil increased 800% between 2013 and 2016.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The network, along with Esporte Interativo, airs games there on cable television.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] NFL had expressed interest in having games in the country, eventually resulting in São Paulo's Arena Corinthians hosting Brazil's first NFL game in 2024, and the Super Bowl has become a widely watched event in Brazil at bars and movie theaters.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Further countries have also expressed interest in football to a lesser degree.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The Arab world has expressed growing interest in American football, with many countries in the region being members of IFAF Asia.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Jordan and the United Arab Emirates, which are not members of IFAF, have established their own domestic leagues.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Egypt established two leagues for the sport, namely the Egyptian League of American Football and the Egyptian Federation of American Football, and Saudi Arabia hosts two teams based out of Jeddah and Yanbu respectively.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] China has additionally been a target for the expansion of the sport, with the Mainland being the home of the Chinese National Football League as well as a growing audience of Super Bowl watchers.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Three franchises are also based out of Hong Kong, which prior to the COVID-19 pandemic regularly played mainland teams.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] NFL games average 900,000 viewers in China, though the league has cited logistical challenges which would prevent teams from playing games akin to abroad games in European countries.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Canadian football, the predominant form of football in Canada, is closely related to American football—both sports developed from rugby and are considered to be the chief variants of gridiron football.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The Canadian Football League (CFL) is the major Canadian league and is the second-most popular sporting league in Canada, behind the National Hockey League.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Football Canada is the governing body for amateur Canadian football, and is also member of the International Federation of American Football.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] NFL players have played in the CFL and vice versa; quarterback Warren Moon is the only player in both Canadian Football Hall of Fame and the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The NFL and CFL had a formal working relationship from 1997 to 2006.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The CFL has a strategic partnership with two American football leagues, the German Football League (GFL) and the Liga de Futbol Americano Profesional (LFA).
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Rule changes announced in 2025 by the CFL will bring some elements of the sport closer to those of American football, while retaining the larger number of players, wider field, and three-down limit.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The Indoor Football League is an example of a prominent indoor league.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] The Arena Football League, which was founded in 1987 and ceased operations in 2019, was one of the longest-lived indoor football leagues.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] In 2004, the league was called "America's fifth major sport" by *ESPN The Magazine*.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Some schools that lack the enrollment numbers to run a competitive 11-man team choose to play nine-man, eight-man, or six-man football, which utilize modified rules to account for smaller team sizes.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] There are several non-contact variants of football, such as flag football.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] In flag football the ball-carrier is not tackled; instead, defenders aim to pull a flag tied around the ball-carrier's waist.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Flag football has become increasingly popular due to its lower likelihood of head injuries and its openness to female athletes; according to the NFL, which promotes flag football through NFL Flag, roughly 25% of flag football players are women and girls.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Another variant, touch football, simply requires the ball-carrier to be touched to be considered downed.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Depending on the rules used, a game of touch football may require the ball-carrier be touched with either one or two hands to be considered downed.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Wheelchair football is a parasport adapting the rules of football for people with physical disabilities.
[src:home-sports/american-football-p02] Although it uses touch rules instead of tackling, wheelchair football isn't a non-contact sport; participants engage in both "big hits" and "physical blocks".
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The **National Arena** (Romanian: *Arena Națională*) is a retractable roof football stadium in Bucharest, Romania.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] It opened in 2011 on the site of the original National Stadium, which was demolished between 2007 and 2008.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The stadium hosts major football matches including home matches of the Romania National Football Team, and usually Romanian Cup Final.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] With 55,634 seats, it is the largest stadium in Romania.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] Designed by Gerkan, Marg and Partners, the stadium was built by Max Bögl and Astaldi firms.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The stadium has a retractable roof which covers the playing surface.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] In addition to Romania home games and the Romanian Cup final, the stadium also hosts other major games in Romanian football, including the season-opening Supercupa României.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] A UEFA category four stadium, the National Arena hosted the 2012 UEFA Europa League final, and four games at UEFA Euro 2020 (including the Round of 16 match between France and Switzerland, ended in a 3–3 draw, with Switzerland defeating France 5–4 at penalties).
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The stadium has also been used as the venue for The International 2021, the annual *Dota 2* world championship event that still holds the Guinness World Records for the largest Esports prize pool for a single tournament ($40,018,195).
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] Arena Națională has hosted concerts by Metallica, Guns N' Roses, Red Hot Chili Peppers, Depeche Mode, and Ed Sheeran.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The Arena Națională is currently the home ground of FCSB, the biggest brand in Romanian football.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] FC Dinamo București also plays some selected matches at the Arena Națională.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The old stadium was demolished between 18 December 2007 and 20 February 2008, although a symbolic removal of seats took place on 21 November 2007, after Romania defeated Albania 6–1 in a qualifying match for Euro 2008.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The construction phase generated some controversy over costs and delays, with Bucharest mayor Sorin Oprescu claiming that the works were 20 weeks behind schedule in May 2009.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] On 8 October 2009, it was decided that the stadium should also include a retractable roof worth €20,000,000.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] Construction was temporarily halted in December 2009 due to unfavorable weather conditions.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] 3,600 VIP seats are available, with another 126 seats allotted for the press (with a possible expansion to 548 seats).
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The stadium includes some 360 restrooms and a retractable roof, which can be opened or closed in 15 minutes.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] It is also endowed with a floodlight system and 2100 parking spaces.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The stadium is also very similar to the Kazimierz Górski National Stadium in Warsaw, Poland, in terms of age, capacity and the roof.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The National Stadium is a Category 4 venue and as such, it hosted the UEFA Europa League 2011–12 final, as announced by UEFA at Nyon on 29 January 2009.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] It was required to host at least two major events beginning in July 2011, one with an attendance of 10,000 and the second with an attendance of at least 40,000.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The stadium also hosted The International 2021, the annual world championship for the video game *Dota 2*, in October 2021.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] This came after the original hosts, Sweden, did not classify esports as a sporting event, making it more difficult for players to procure visas to the country.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The official inauguration was initially scheduled for 10 August 2011, and was to feature a football match between Romania and Argentina.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] However, on 26 July, Argentina officially cancelled the friendly match after their manager Sergio Batista departed the team.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The stadium was inaugurated on 6 September 2011, with a UEFA Euro 2012 Group D qualifier match between Romania and France.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] In the front of 49,137 fans, Romania and France drew 0–0.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The result meant that Romania lost any chance of qualifying for the tournament, hosted by neighbours Ukraine and Poland.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The highest audience for a football match was achieved at an exhibition game between Romania's "Golden Generation" and the "World Stars" team, ended with a 3–2 score, which brought 54.967 spectators at the stadium.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] It was the retirement match of arguably the best Romanian national team ever.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The second highest audience for a football game was achieved at the Liga 1 football match between FCSB and CFR Cluj hosted on 11 May 2024, which brought 54,673 people to the stadium.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] Another large audience was hosted at the UEFA Europa League final on 9 May 2012.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The game between the two Spanish teams, Atlético Madrid and Athletic Bilbao, brought 52,347 people to the stadium.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] Another match with a notable audience was between Romania and Switzerland on 21 November 2023, in the qualifying stage of the UEFA Euro 2024 final tournament.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] With 50,224 people in the stands, Romania won 1–0, thus making it the winner of Group I and giving it a place in Pot 2 for the final tournament in Germany.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The match was played behind closed doors due to COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] On 6 September 2011, the Romania national football team, played the opening match against the French team which ended with a goalless draw, after Argentina cancelled the official inauguration, a friendly match between Romania and Argentina on 10 August 2011.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] Arena Națională was one of the stadiums that hosted matches for the UEFA Euro 2020.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] Three Group C matches and a Round of 16 game were played there.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The stadium is served by public transport with buses, trolleybuses, trams and the subway system.
[src:home-sports/arena-națională] The nearest subway station (Piata Muncii) is about 1.7 km away (a 22-minute walk).
[src:home-sports/association-football] The objective of the game is to score more goals than the opposing team by moving the ball beyond the goal line into a rectangular-framed goal defended by the opponent.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Traditionally, the game has been played over two 45-minute halves, for a total match time of 90 minutes.
[src:home-sports/association-football] With an estimated 250 million players active in over 200 countries and territories, it is the world's most popular sport.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Association football is played in accordance with the Laws of the Game, a set of rules that has been in effect since 1863 and maintained by the International Football Association Board (IFAB) since 1886.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The game is played with a football that is 68–70 cm (27–28 in) in circumference.
[src:home-sports/association-football] When the ball is in play, the players mainly use their feet, but may also use any other part of their body, except for their hands or arms, to control, strike, or pass the ball; the head, chest, and thighs are commonly used.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Only the goalkeepers may use their hands and arms, but only within their own penalty area.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Depending on the format of the competition, an equal number of goals scored may result in a draw being declared with 1 point awarded to each team, or the game may go into extra time or a penalty shoot-out.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Internationally, association football is governed by FIFA.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Under FIFA, there are six continental confederations: AFC, CAF, CONCACAF, CONMEBOL, OFC, and UEFA.
[src:home-sports/association-football] National associations (e.g. the FA in England, U.S.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Soccer in the United States, etc.) are responsible for managing the game in their own countries both professionally and at an amateur level, and coordinating competitions in accordance with the Laws of the Game.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The most prestigious senior international competition is the FIFA World Cup.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The men's World Cup is the most-viewed sporting event in the world, surpassing the Olympic Games.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The most prestigious competition in European club football is the UEFA Champions League, which attracts an extensive television audience worldwide.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The final of the men's Champions League is the most-watched annual sporting event in the world.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Association football is part of a family of football games that emerged from various ball games played worldwide since antiquity.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The word "association" in this term refers to the Football Association (the FA), founded in London in 1863, which published the first set of rules for the sport that same year.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The term was coined to distinguish the type of football played in accordance with the FA rules from other types that were gaining popularity at the time, particularly rugby football.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The term *soccer* comes from Oxford "-er" slang, which was prevalent at the University of Oxford in England from about 1875, and is thought to have been borrowed from the slang of Rugby School.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Initially spelt *assoccer* (a shortening of "association"), it was later reduced to the modern spelling.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Early alternative spellings included *socca* and *socker*.
[src:home-sports/association-football] This form of slang also gave rise to *rugger* for rugby football, *fiver* and *tenner* for five pound and ten pound notes, and the now-archaic *footer* that was also a name for association football.
[src:home-sports/association-football] A notable exception is New Zealand, where in the first two decades of the 21st century, under the influence of international television, "football" has been gaining prevalence, despite the dominance of other types of football, namely rugby union and rugby league.
[src:home-sports/association-football] FIFA has stated that soccer originated in Britain, starting around the eighth century, and that no historical connection exists with any game played in antiquity outside Europe.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The modern rules of association football are based on the mid-19th century efforts to standardise the widely varying forms of football played in the public schools of England.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Kicking ball games arose independently multiple times across multiple cultures.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The Chinese competitive game **cuju** (蹴鞠, literally "kickball"; also known as *tsu chu*) resembles modern association football as well as a mix of basketball and volleyball.
[src:home-sports/association-football] This is the earliest form of a kicking game for which there is historical evidence.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The game was first recorded as in exercise in the Zhan Guo Ce, a military history from the Han dynasty.
[src:home-sports/association-football] **Cuju** players would pass the ball around, having to avoid it touching the ground at any point.
[src:home-sports/association-football] It was then passed to a designated player, who attempted to kick it through the *fengliu yan*, a circular goal atop 10–11 meter poles.
[src:home-sports/association-football] During the Han dynasty (206 BCE – 220 CE), **cuju** games were standardised and rules were established.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The Silk Road facilitated the transmission of *cuju* outside of China, especially the form of the game popular in the Tang dynasty, the period when the inflatable ball was invented and replaced the stuffed ball.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Other East Asian games include **kemari** in Japan and **chuk-guk** in Korea, both influenced by *cuju*.
[src:home-sports/association-football] **Kemari** originated after the year 600 during the Asuka period.
[src:home-sports/association-football] It was a ceremonial rather than a competitive game, and involved the kicking of a *mari*, a ball made of animal skin.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In North America, *pasuckuakohowog* was a ball game played by the Algonquians; it was described as "almost identical to the kind of folk football being played in Europe at the same time, in which the ball was kicked through goals".
[src:home-sports/association-football] In the Middle Ages, one notable game with similarities to modern football was *calcio storico fiorentino*, which originated in Florence, Italy.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Another medieval sport that can be considered a form of early football is *la soule* (or *choule*), played in France from the 12th century, in which the ball was propelled by hands, feet, and sticks.
[src:home-sports/association-football] As with pre-codified mob football, the antecedent of all modern football codes, these medieval games involved more handling of the ball than kicking it.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The Cambridge rules, first drawn up at the University of Cambridge in 1848, were particularly influential in the development of subsequent codes, including association football.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The Cambridge rules were written at Trinity College, Cambridge, at a meeting attended by representatives from Eton, Harrow, Rugby, Winchester, and Shrewsbury schools.
[src:home-sports/association-football] During the 1850s, many clubs unconnected to schools or universities were formed throughout the English-speaking world to play various forms of football.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Some came up with their own distinct codes of rules, most notably the Sheffield Football Club, formed by former public school pupils in 1857, which led to the formation of a Sheffield FA in 1867.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In 1862, John Charles Thring of Uppingham School also devised an influential set of rules.
[src:home-sports/association-football] These ongoing efforts contributed to the formation of the Football Association (the FA) in 1863, which first met on the morning of 26 October 1863 at the Freemasons' Tavern in Great Queen Street, London.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The only school to be represented on this occasion was Charterhouse.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The Freemasons' Tavern was the setting for five more meetings of the FA between October and December 1863; the English FA eventually issued the first comprehensive set of rules named Laws of the Game, forming modern football.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The laws included bans on running with the ball in hand and hacking (kicking an opponent in the shins), tripping and holding.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Eleven clubs, under the charge of FA secretary Ebenezer Cobb Morley, ratified the original thirteen laws of the game.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The sticking point was hacking, which a twelfth club at the meeting, Blackheath FC, had wanted to keep, resulting in their withdrawal from the FA.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Other English rugby clubs followed this lead and did not join the FA, and instead in 1871, along with Blackheath, formed the Rugby Football Union.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The 1863 FA rules included handling of the ball by "marks" and the lack of a crossbar, making the game remarkably similar to Victorian rules football, which was being developed around the same time in Australia.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The Sheffield FA played by its own rules until the 1870s, with the FA absorbing some of its rules until there was little difference between the games.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The world's oldest football competition is the FA Cup, which was founded by the footballer and cricketer Charles W.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Alcock, and has been contested by English teams since 1872.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The first official international football match also took place in 1872, between Scotland and England in Glasgow, again at the instigation of Alcock.
[src:home-sports/association-football] England is also home to the world's first football league, which was founded in Birmingham in 1888 by Aston Villa director William McGregor.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The original format contained 12 clubs from the Midlands and Northern England.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The Laws of the Game are determined by the International Football Association Board (IFAB).
[src:home-sports/association-football] The board was formed in 1886 after a meeting in Manchester of the Football Association, the Scottish Football Association, the Football Association of Wales, and the Irish Football Association.
[src:home-sports/association-football] FIFA, the international football body, was formed in Paris in 1904 and declared that they would adhere to the Laws of the Game of the Football Association.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The growing popularity of the international game led to the admittance of FIFA representatives to the IFAB in 1913.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The board consists of four representatives from FIFA and one representative from each of the four British associations.
[src:home-sports/association-football] For most of the 20th century, Europe and South America were the dominant regions in association football.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The FIFA World Cup, inaugurated in 1930, became the main stage for players of both continents to show their worth and the strength of their national teams.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In the second half of the century, the European Cup and the Copa Libertadores were created, and the champions of these two club competitions would contest the Intercontinental Cup to prove which team was the best in the world.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In the 21st century, South America has continued to produce some of the best footballers in the world, but its clubs have fallen behind the still dominant European clubs, which often sign the best players from Latin America and elsewhere.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Meanwhile, football has improved in Africa, Asia, and North America, and nowadays, these regions are at least on equal grounds with South America in club football.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Football is played at a professional level all over the world.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Millions of people regularly go to football stadiums to follow their favourite teams, whilst billions more watch the game on television or on the internet.
[src:home-sports/association-football] A very large number of people also play football at an amateur level.
[src:home-sports/association-football] According to a survey conducted by FIFA published in 2001, over 240 million people from more than 200 countries regularly play football.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Football has the highest global television audience in sport.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In many parts of the world, football evokes great passions and plays an important role in the life of individual fans, local communities, and even nations.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Ryszard Kapuściński says that Europeans who are polite, modest, or humble fall easily into rage when playing or watching football games.
[src:home-sports/association-football] By contrast, football is widely considered to have been the final proximate cause for the Football War in June 1969 between El Salvador and Honduras.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The sport also exacerbated tensions at the beginning of the Croatian War of Independence of the 1990s, when a match between Dinamo Zagreb and Red Star Belgrade degenerated into rioting in May 1990.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The popularity of association football has been connected to identity fusion with replacement fandom collective identities.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Women's association football has historically seen opposition, with national associations severely curbing its development and several outlawing it completely.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Nevertheless, women have been playing football and similar games for as long as such games have existed.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Frescoes from the Han dynasty (25–220 CE) depict female figures playing the ancient Chinese game *cuju*.
[src:home-sports/association-football] There are also reports of annual football matches played by women in Midlothian, Scotland, during the 1790s.
[src:home-sports/association-football] There is documented evidence of women's early involvement in association football.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Informal matches between Scotland and England are reported to have taken place in 1881, but are not officially recognised by the respective football associations.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The first women's match recorded by the Scottish Football Association took place in 1892 in Glasgow.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In England, the first recorded game of football between women took place in 1895.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The best-documented early European team was founded by activist Nettie Honeyball in England in 1894: the British Ladies' Football Club.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Honeyball considered women's involvement in football as part of the emancipation movement.
[src:home-sports/association-football] She and others like her paved the way for women's football.
[src:home-sports/association-football] However, the women's game was frowned upon by the British football associations and continued without their support.
[src:home-sports/association-football] It has been suggested that this was motivated by a perceived threat to the "masculinity" of the game.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Women's football became popular on a large scale at the time of the First World War, when female employment in heavy industry spurred the growth of the game, much as it had done for men decades earlier.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The most successful team of the era was Dick, Kerr Ladies F.C. of Preston, England.
[src:home-sports/association-football] They played in one of the first women's international matches against a French XI team in 1920, and also made up most of the England team against a Scottish Ladies XI in the same year, winning 22–0.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In the early 20th century, women's football in the United Kingdom was mostly associated with charity matches.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Players and football writers have argued that this ban was, in fact, due to envy of the large crowds that women's matches attracted, and because the FA had no control over the money made from the women's game.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The FA ban led to the formation of the short-lived English Ladies Football Association and play moved to rugby grounds.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Women's football also faced bans in several other countries, notably in Brazil from 1941 to 1979, in France from 1941 to 1970, and in West Germany from 1955 to 1970.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In spite of the resistance from governing bodies, British women continued to play football.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Restrictions against female participation in the sport began to be reduced in the late 1960s and the 1970s.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The Italian women's football league was established in 1968.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In December 1969, the Women's Football Association was formed in England, with the sport eventually becoming the most prominent team sport for women in the United Kingdom.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Two unofficial women's World Cups were organised by the FIEFF in 1970 and in 1971.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Also in 1971, UEFA members voted to officially recognise women's football, while the Football Association rescinded the ban that prohibited women from playing on association members' pitches in England.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The first Asian Women's Championship happened in 1975, initially without the approval of the AFC, but later recognised by them.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Women's football still faces many struggles, but its worldwide growth has seen major competitions being launched at both the national and international levels, mirroring the men's competitions.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The FIFA Women's World Cup was inaugurated in 1991: the first tournament was held in China, featuring 12 teams from the six confederations.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The World Cup has been held every four years since; by 2019, it had expanded to 24 national teams, and 1.12 billion viewers watched the competition.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Four years later, FIFA targeted the 32-team 2023 Women's World Cup at an audience of 2 billion, while more than 1.5 million tickets were sold, setting a Women's World Cup record.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Women's football has been an Olympic event since 1996.
[src:home-sports/association-football] North America is the dominant region in women's football, with the United States winning the most FIFA Women's World Cups and Olympic tournaments.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Europe and Asia come second and third in terms of international success, and the women's game has been improving in South America.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Association football is played in accordance with a set of rules known as the Laws of the Game.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The game is played using a spherical ball of 68–70 cm (27–28 in) circumference, known as the *football* (or *soccer ball*).
[src:home-sports/association-football] Two teams of eleven players each compete to get the ball into the other team's goal (between the posts and under the bar), thereby scoring a goal.
[src:home-sports/association-football] There are situations where a goal can be disallowed, such as an offside call or a foul in the build-up to the goal.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The team that has scored more goals at the end of the game is the winner; if both teams have scored an equal number of goals then the game is a draw.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Each team is led by a captain who has only one official responsibility as mandated by the Laws of the Game: to represent their team in the coin toss before kick-off or penalty kicks.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The primary law is that players other than goalkeepers may not deliberately handle the ball with their hands or arms during play, though they must use both their hands during a throw-in restart.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Although players usually use their feet to move the ball around, they may use any part of their body (notably, "heading" with the forehead) other than their hands or arms.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Within normal play, all players are free to play the ball in any direction and move throughout the pitch, though players may not pass to teammates who are in an offside position.
[src:home-sports/association-football] During gameplay, players attempt to create goal-scoring opportunities through individual control of the ball, such as by dribbling, passing the ball to a teammate, and by taking shots at the goal, which is guarded by the opposing goalkeeper.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Opposing players may try to regain control of the ball by intercepting a pass or through tackling the opponent in possession of the ball; however, physical contact between opponents is restricted.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Football is generally a free-flowing game, with play stopping only when the ball has left the field of play or when play is stopped by the referee for an infringement of the rules.
[src:home-sports/association-football] After a stoppage, play recommences with a specified restart.
[src:home-sports/association-football] At a professional level, most matches produce only a few goals.
[src:home-sports/association-football] For example, the 2022–23 season of the English Premier League produced an average of 2.85 goals per match.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The Laws of the Game do not specify any player positions other than goalkeeper, but a number of specialised roles have evolved.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Broadly, these include three main categories: strikers, or forwards, whose main task is to score goals; defenders, who specialise in preventing their opponents from scoring; and midfielders, who dispossess the opposition and keep possession of the ball to pass it to the forwards on their team.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Players in these positions are referred to as outfield players, to distinguish them from the goalkeeper.
[src:home-sports/association-football] These positions are further subdivided according to the area of the field in which the player spends the most time.
[src:home-sports/association-football] For example, there are central defenders and left and right midfielders.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The ten outfield players may be arranged in any combination.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The number of players in each position determines the style of the team's play; more forwards and fewer defenders creates a more aggressive and offensive-minded game, while the reverse creates a slower, more defensive style of play.
[src:home-sports/association-football] While players typically spend most of the game in a specific position, there are few restrictions on player movement, and players can switch positions at any time.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The layout of a team's players is known as a *formation*.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Defining the team's formation and tactics is usually the prerogative of the team's manager.
[src:home-sports/association-football] There are seventeen laws in the official Laws of the Game, each containing a collection of stipulations and guidelines.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The same laws are designed to apply to all levels of football for both sexes, although certain modifications for groups such as juniors, seniors and people with physical disabilities are permitted.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The laws are often framed in broad terms, which allow flexibility in their application depending on the nature of the game.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The Laws of the Game are published by FIFA, but are maintained by the IFAB.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In addition to the seventeen laws, numerous IFAB decisions and other directives contribute to the regulation of association football.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Within the United States, Major League Soccer used a distinct ruleset during the 1990s, and the NFHS and NCAA still use rulesets that are comparable to, but different from, the IFAB Laws.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Each team consists of a maximum of eleven players (excluding substitutes), one of whom must be the goalkeeper.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Competition rules may state a minimum number of players required to constitute a team, which is usually seven.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Goalkeepers are the only players allowed to play the ball with their hands or arms, provided they do so within the penalty area in front of their own goal.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Though there are a variety of positions in which the outfield (non-goalkeeper) players are strategically placed by a coach, these positions are not defined or required by the Laws.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The basic equipment or *kit* players are required to wear includes a shirt, shorts, socks, footwear and adequate shin guards.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Wearing an athletic supporter with protective cup is recommended for male players by medical experts and professionals.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Headgear is not a required piece of equipment, but players may choose to wear it to protect themselves from head injury.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Players are forbidden to wear or use anything that is dangerous to themselves or another player, such as jewellery or watches.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The goalkeeper must wear clothing that is easily distinguishable from that worn by the other players and the match officials.
[src:home-sports/association-football] A number of players may be replaced by substitutes during the course of the game.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The maximum number of substitutions permitted in most competitive international and domestic league games is five in 90 minutes, with each team being allowed one more if the game should go into extra-time; the permitted number may vary in other competitions or in friendly matches.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Common reasons for a substitution include injury, tiredness, ineffectiveness, a tactical switch, or timewasting at the end of a finely poised game.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In standard adult matches, a player who has been substituted may not take further part in a match.
[src:home-sports/association-football] IFAB recommends "that a match should not continue if there are fewer than seven players in either team".
[src:home-sports/association-football] Any decision regarding points awarded for abandoned games is left to the individual football associations.
[src:home-sports/association-football] A game is officiated by a referee, who has "full authority to enforce the Laws of the Game in connection with the match to which he has been appointed" (Law 5), and whose decisions are final.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The referee is assisted by two assistant referees.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In many high-level games there is also a fourth official who assists the referee and may replace another official should the need arise.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Goal line technology is used to measure if the whole ball has crossed the goal-line thereby determining whether a goal has been scored or not; this was brought in to prevent controversy.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Video assistant referees (VAR) have also been increasingly introduced in high-level matches to assist officials through video replays to correct clear and obvious mistakes.
[src:home-sports/association-football] There are four types of calls that can be reviewed: mistaken identity in awarding a red or yellow card, goals and whether there was a violation during the build-up, direct red card decisions, and penalty decisions.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The ball is spherical with a circumference of between 68 and 70 cm (27 and 28 in), a weight in the range of 410 to 450 g (14 to 16 oz), and a pressure between 0.6 and 1.1 standard atmospheres (8.5 and 15.6 pounds per square inch) at sea level.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In the past the ball was made up of leather panels sewn together, with a latex bladder for pressurisation, but modern balls at all levels of the game are now synthetic.
[src:home-sports/association-football] As the Laws were formulated in England, and were initially administered solely by the four British football associations within IFAB, the standard dimensions of a football pitch were originally expressed in imperial units.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The Laws now express dimensions with approximate metric equivalents (followed by traditional units in brackets), though use of imperial units remains popular in English-speaking countries with a relatively recent history of metrication (or only partial metrication), such as Britain.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The length of the pitch, or field, for international adult matches is in the range of 100–110 m (110–120 yd) and the width is in the range of 64–75 m (70–80 yd).
[src:home-sports/association-football] Fields for non-international matches may be 90–120 m (100–130 yd) in length and 45–90 m (50–100 yd) in width, provided the pitch does not become square.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In 2008, the IFAB initially approved a fixed size of 105 m (115 yd) long and 68 m (74 yd) wide as a standard pitch dimension for international matches; however, this decision was later put on hold and was never actually implemented.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The longer boundary lines are *touchlines*, while the shorter boundaries (on which the goals are placed) are *goal lines*.
[src:home-sports/association-football] A rectangular goal is positioned on each goal line, midway between the two touchlines.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The inner edges of the vertical goal posts must be 7.32 m (24 ft) apart, and the lower edge of the horizontal crossbar supported by the goal posts must be 2.44 m (8 ft) above the ground.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Nets are usually placed behind the goal, but are not required by the Laws.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In front of the goal is the penalty area.
[src:home-sports/association-football] This area is marked by the goal line, two lines starting on the goal line 16.5 m (18 yd) from the goalposts and extending 16.5 m (18 yd) into the pitch perpendicular to the goal line, and a line joining them.
[src:home-sports/association-football] This area has a number of functions, the most prominent being to mark where the goalkeeper may handle the ball and where a penalty foul by a member of the defending team becomes punishable by a penalty kick.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Other markings define the position of the ball or players at kick-offs, goal kicks, penalty kicks and corner kicks.
[src:home-sports/association-football] A standard adult football match consists of two halves of 45 minutes each.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Each half runs continuously, meaning that the clock is not stopped when the ball is out of play.
[src:home-sports/association-football] There is usually a 15-minute half-time break between halves.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The end of the match is known as full-time.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The referee is the official timekeeper for the match, and may make an allowance for time lost through substitutions, injured players requiring attention, or other stoppages.
[src:home-sports/association-football] This added time is called "additional time" in FIFA documents, but is most commonly referred to as *stoppage time* or *injury time*, while *lost time* can also be used as a synonym.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The duration of stoppage time is at the sole discretion of the referee.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Stoppage time does not fully compensate for the time in which the ball is out of play, and a 90-minute game typically involves about an hour of "effective playing time".
[src:home-sports/association-football] The referee alone signals the end of the match.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In matches where a fourth official is appointed, towards the end of the half, the referee signals how many minutes of stoppage time they intend to add.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The fourth official then informs the players and spectators by holding up a board showing this number.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The signalled stoppage time may be further extended by the referee.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Added time was introduced because of an incident in 1891 during a match between Stoke and Aston Villa.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Trailing 1–0 with two minutes remaining, Stoke were awarded a penalty kick.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Villa's goalkeeper deliberately kicked the ball far out of play; by the time it was recovered, the clock had run out and the game was over, leaving Stoke unable to attempt the penalty.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The same rule also states that the duration of either half is extended until a penalty kick to be taken or retaken is completed; thus, no game can end with an uncompleted penalty.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Due to the relatively high ambient temperatures in some regions, cooling breaks for the players were introduced.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Breaks could take place at the referee's discretion after the 30th minute of each half if the wet-bulb globe temperature exceeded 32 °C (90 °F); the breaks would last 3 minutes, with this time made up by an extended period of stoppage time at the end of the half.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In league competitions, games may end in a draw.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In knockout competitions where a winner is required, various methods may be employed to break such a deadlock; some competitions may invoke replays.
[src:home-sports/association-football] A game tied at the end of regulation time may go into extra time, which consists of two further 15-minute periods.
[src:home-sports/association-football] If the score is still tied after extra time, some competitions allow the use of penalty shoot-outs (previously known in the Laws of the Game as "kicks from the penalty mark") to determine which team will progress to the next stage of the tournament or be the champion.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Goals scored during extra time periods count towards the final score of the game, but kicks from the penalty mark are only used to decide the team that progresses to the next part of the tournament, with goals scored in a penalty shoot-out not making up part of the final score.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In competitions using two-legged matches, each team competes at home once, with an aggregate score from the two matches deciding which team progresses.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Where aggregates are equal, the away goals rule may be used to determine the winners, in which case the winner is the team that scored the most goals in the leg they played away from home.
[src:home-sports/association-football] If the result is still equal, extra time and potentially a penalty shoot-out are required.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Under the Laws, the two basic states of play during a game are *ball in play* and *ball out of play*.
[src:home-sports/association-football] From the beginning of each playing period with a kick-off until the end of the playing period, the ball is in play at all times, except when either the ball leaves the field of play, or play is stopped by the referee.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Players are cautioned with a yellow card, and dismissed from the game with a red card.
[src:home-sports/association-football] A foul occurs when a player commits an offence listed in the Laws of the Game while the ball is in play.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The offences that constitute a foul are listed in Law 12.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Handling the ball deliberately, tripping an opponent, or pushing an opponent, are examples of "penal fouls", punishable by a direct free kick or penalty kick depending on where the offence occurred.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Other fouls are punishable by an indirect free kick.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The referee may punish a player's or substitute's misconduct by a caution (yellow card) or dismissal (red card).
[src:home-sports/association-football] A second yellow card in the same game leads to a red card, which results in a dismissal.
[src:home-sports/association-football] A player given a yellow card is said to have been "booked", the referee writing the player's name in their official notebook.
[src:home-sports/association-football] If a player has been dismissed, no substitute can be brought on in their place and the player may not participate in further play.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Misconduct may occur at any time, and while the offences that constitute misconduct are listed, the definitions are broad.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In particular, the offence of "unsporting behaviour" may be used to deal with most events that violate the spirit of the game, even if they are not listed as specific offences.
[src:home-sports/association-football] A referee can show a yellow or red card to a player, substitute, substituted player, and to non-players such as managers and support staff.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Rather than stopping play, the referee may allow play to continue if doing so will benefit the team against which an offence has been committed.
[src:home-sports/association-football] This is known as "playing an advantage".
[src:home-sports/association-football] The referee may "call back" play and penalise the original offence if the anticipated advantage does not ensue within "a few seconds".
[src:home-sports/association-football] Even if an offence is not penalised due to advantage being played, the offender may still be sanctioned for misconduct at the next stoppage of play.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The referee's decision in all on-pitch matters is considered final.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The score of a match cannot be altered after the game, even if later evidence shows that decisions (including whether a goal was awarded or not) were incorrect.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Along with the general administration of the sport, football associations and competition organisers also enforce good conduct in wider aspects of the game, dealing with issues such as comments to the press, clubs' financial management, doping, age fraud and match fixing.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Most competitions enforce mandatory suspensions for players who are sent off in a game.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Some on-field incidents, if considered very serious (such as allegations of racial abuse), may result in competitions deciding to impose heavier sanctions than those normally associated with a red card.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Some associations allow for appeals against player suspensions incurred on-field if clubs feel a referee was incorrect or unduly harsh.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Sanctions for such infractions may be levied on individuals or on clubs as a whole.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Penalties may include fines, point deductions (in league competitions) or even expulsion from competitions.
[src:home-sports/association-football] For example, the English Football League deduct 12 points from any team that enters financial administration.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Among other administrative sanctions are penalties against game forfeiture.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Teams that forfeit a game or are forfeited against are awarded a technical loss or win.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The recognised international governing body of football (and associated games, such as futsal and beach soccer) is FIFA.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The FIFA headquarters are located in Zürich, Switzerland.
[src:home-sports/association-football] National associations (or national federations) oversee football within individual countries.
[src:home-sports/association-football] 211 national associations are affiliated both with FIFA and with their respective continental confederations.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Other national associations may be members of continental confederations but otherwise not participate in FIFA competitions.
[src:home-sports/association-football] While FIFA is responsible for organising international competitions and enforcing most international regulations, the Laws of the Game are set by the IFAB, where each of the four UK associations holds one vote and FIFA collectively holds four votes.
[src:home-sports/association-football] International competitions in association football principally consist of two varieties: competitions involving representative national teams or those involving clubs based in multiple nations and national leagues.
[src:home-sports/association-football] *International football*, without qualification, most often refers to the former.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In the case of international club competition, it is the country of origin of the clubs involved, not the nationalities of their players, that renders the competition international in nature.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The major international competition in football and the most prestigious is the World Cup, organised by FIFA.
[src:home-sports/association-football] This competition has taken place every four years since 1930, with the exception of the 1942 and 1946 tournaments, which were cancelled because of World War II.
[src:home-sports/association-football] As of 2022, over 200 national teams compete in qualifying tournaments within the scope of continental confederations for a place in the finals.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The finals tournament involved 32 national teams (expanding to 48 teams for the 2026 tournament) competing over a four-week period.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The World Cup is the world's most widely viewed and most followed sporting event, with the 2022 tournament estimated to be watched by 5 billion people, more than 60% of the global population.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The 1958 World Cup saw the emergence of Pelé as a global sporting star, a period that coincided with "the explosive spread of television, which massively amplified his presence everywhere".
[src:home-sports/association-football] The current champions are Argentina, who won their third title at the 2022 tournament in Qatar.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The FIFA Women's World Cup has been held every four years since 1991.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Under the tournament's current format that was expanded in 2023, national teams vie for 31 slots in a three-year qualification phase, while the host nation's team enters automatically as the 32nd slot.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The current champions are Spain, after winning their first title in the 2023 tournament.
[src:home-sports/association-football] There has been a football tournament at every Summer Olympic Games since 1900, except at the 1932 games in Los Angeles when FIFA and the International Olympic Committee (IOC) had disagreed over the status of amateur players.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Before the inception of the World Cup, the Olympics (especially during the 1920s) were the most prestigious international event.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Originally, the tournament was for amateurs only.
[src:home-sports/association-football] As professionalism spread around the world, the gap in quality between the World Cup and the Olympics widened.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The countries that benefited most were the Soviet Bloc countries of Eastern Europe, where top athletes were state-sponsored while retaining their status as amateurs.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Between 1948 and 1980, 23 out of 27 Olympic medals were won by Eastern Europe, with only Sweden (gold in 1948 and bronze in 1952), Denmark (bronze in 1948 and silver in 1960) and Japan (bronze in 1968) breaking their dominance.
[src:home-sports/association-football] For the 1984 Los Angeles Games, the IOC allowed professional players to compete.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Since 1992, male competitors must be under 23 years old, although since 1996, three players over the age of 23 have been allowed per squad.
[src:home-sports/association-football] A women's tournament was added in 1996; in contrast to the men's event, full international sides without age restrictions play the women's Olympic tournament.
[src:home-sports/association-football] After the World Cup, the most important international football competitions are the continental championships, which are organised by each continental confederation and contested between national teams.
[src:home-sports/association-football] These are the European Championship (UEFA), the Copa América (CONMEBOL), the Africa Cup of Nations (CAF), the Asian Cup (AFC), the Gold Cup (CONCACAF) and the Nations Cup (OFC).
[src:home-sports/association-football] These competitions are not strictly limited to members of the continental confederations, with guest teams from other continents sometimes invited to compete.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The FIFA Confederations Cup was contested by the winners of all six continental championships, the current FIFA World Cup champions, and the country which was hosting the next World Cup.
[src:home-sports/association-football] This was generally regarded as a warm-up tournament for the upcoming FIFA World Cup and did not carry the same prestige as the World Cup itself.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The tournament was discontinued following the 2017 edition, with its calendar slot replaced by an expanded FIFA Club World Cup.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The Finalissima was revived in 2022, and is contested between the Copa América and European Championship winners.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The UEFA Nations League and the CONCACAF Nations League were introduced in the late 2010s to replace international friendlies during the two-year cycle between major tournaments.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The most prestigious competitions in club football are the respective continental championships, which are generally contested between national champions, for example, the UEFA Champions League in Europe and the Copa Libertadores in South America.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The winners of each continental competition contest the FIFA Intercontinental Cup, held annually, and the FIFA Club World Cup, held once every four years.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In each country, football clubs are usually federated in associations or leagues that organise official tournaments among themselves, from which the champion of each country and the teams that will participate in international club tournaments emerge.
[src:home-sports/association-football] There is no single system of competitions, and each national league organises them according to its own traditions.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The governing bodies in each country operate league systems in a domestic season, normally comprising several divisions, in which the teams gain points throughout the season depending on results, usually three points for a win, one for a draw and zero for a defeat.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Teams are put into tables, placed in order according to points accrued.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In the Old World (Africa, Asia and Europe), it is common for each team to play every other team in its league at home and away in each season, in a round-robin tournament.
[src:home-sports/association-football] At the end of a season, which typically runs from August to May, the top team is declared the champion.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The top few teams may be promoted to a higher division, and one or more of the teams finishing at the bottom are relegated to a lower division.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The teams finishing at the top of a country's league may also be eligible to play in international club competitions in the following season.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Most countries supplement the league system with one or more "cup" competitions organised on a knock-out basis.
[src:home-sports/association-football] These include the domestic cup, which may be open to all eligible teams in a country's league system—both professional and amateur—and is organised by the national federation.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Some countries' top divisions feature highly-paid star players; in smaller countries, lower divisions, and many women's clubs, players may be part-timers with a second job, or amateurs.
[src:home-sports/association-football] The top five European leagues – Premier League (England), Bundesliga (Germany), La Liga (Spain), Serie A (Italy), and Ligue 1 (France) – attract most of the world's best players and, during the 2006–07 season, each of these leagues had a total wage cost in excess of €600 million.
[src:home-sports/association-football] These leagues also generated a combined €17.2 billion in revenue in the 2021–22 season from television contracts, matchday tickets, sponsorships, and other sources.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In the 2022–23 season, clubs in Europe's "big five" leagues had an aggregate wage cost of €13 billion, with each league spending more than €1.8 billion in wages.
[src:home-sports/association-football] In contrast, the combined revenue of these leagues was €19.6 billion.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Variants of association football have been codified for teams of reduced size, such as five-a-side football; for non-traditional playing environments, including beach soccer, futsal and indoor soccer; and for athletes with disabilities (Paralympic football).
[src:home-sports/association-football] Street football can be played with only minimal equipment – a basic game can be played on almost any open area of reasonable size with just a ball made from almost any material and items to mark the positions of the goalposts.
[src:home-sports/association-football] Such informal games can have team sizes that vary from eleven-a-side, can use a limited or modified subset of the official rules, and can be self-officiated by the players.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Founded on 26 April 1903 as Athletic Club Sucursal de Madrid (a branch of Bilbao-based Athletic Club), the entity merged with Club Aviación Nacional in 1939, becoming Atlético de Madrid in 1946.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] After 1987, Jesús Gil oversaw the transformation from sports club to *sociedad anónima deportiva* (S.A.D.), underpinning his family's control over the shareholding structure through misappropriation.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The club's traditional kits consist of red and white vertical striped shirts and blue shorts.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Followers are nicknamed as *colchoneros* ('mattress makers'), *indios* ('Indians') and *rojiblancos* ('redwhites').
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Prince Felipe, later King Felipe VI, has been the honorary president of the club since 2003.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético are one of the most successful Spanish clubs, having won 11 La Liga titles, including a league and cup double in 1996.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Further domestic trophies include 10 Copa del Rey titles, two Supercopas de España, one Copa Presidente FEF and one Copa Eva Duarte.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] They have also won numerous titles in Europe, including the European Cup Winners' Cup in 1962, the UEFA Europa League in 2010, 2012 and 2018, and the UEFA Super Cup in 2010, 2012 and 2018, in addition to the 1974 Intercontinental Cup.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In the UEFA Champions League, Atlético reached the final in 1974, 2014 and 2016.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] They sustain a standing rivalry with Madrid neighbours Real Madrid, with whom they contest the Madrid derby.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The club was founded on 26 April 1903 as *Athletic Club Sucursal de Madrid* by three Basque students living in Madrid.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] These founders saw the new club as a youth branch of their childhood team, Athletic Bilbao who they had just seen win the 1903 Copa del Rey Final in the city.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In 1904, they were joined by dissident members of Real Madrid.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] They began playing in blue and white halved shirts, the then colours of Athletic Bilbao, but by 1910, both the Bilbao and Madrid teams were playing in their current colours of red and white stripes.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Some believe the change came about because red and white striped tops were the cheapest to make, as the same combination was used to make ticking for mattresses, and the unused cloth was easily converted into football shirts.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] This contributed to the club's nickname, *Los Colchoneros*.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] However, another explanation is that both Athletic Bilbao and Athletic Madrid used to buy Blackburn Rovers' blue and white kits in England.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] An investigation in 2023 proposed an alternative kit origin location as Sunderland, whose team also wore those colours.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Athletic Madrid adopted the red and white shirt, leading to them being known as *Los Rojiblancos*, but opted to keep their existing blue shorts whereas the Bilbao team switched to new black shorts.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Athletic Bilbao won the 1911 Copa del Rey Final using several 'borrowed' players from Athletic Madrid, including Manolón who scored one of their goals.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Athletic's first ground, the Ronda de Vallecas, was in the eponymous working-class area on the south side of the city.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In 1919, the Compañía Urbanizadora Metropolitana—the company that ran the underground communication system in Madrid—acquired some land, near the Ciudad Universitaria.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In 1921, Athletic Madrid became independent of parent-club Athletic Bilbao and moved into a 35,800-seater stadium built by the company, the Estadio Metropolitano de Madrid.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] During the 1920s, Athletic won the *Campeonato del Centro* three times and were Copa del Rey runners-up in 1921, where they faced parent club Athletic Bilbao, as they would again in 1926.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Based on these successes, in 1928 they were invited to join the Primera División of the inaugural La Liga played the following year.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] During their debut La Liga campaign, the club was managed by Fred Pentland, but after two seasons they were relegated to Segunda División.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] They briefly returned to La Liga in 1934 but were relegated again in 1936 after Josep Samitier took over in mid-season from Pentland.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The Spanish Civil War gave *Los Colchoneros* a reprieve, as Real Oviedo was unable to play due to the destruction of their stadium during the bombings.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Thus, both La Liga and Athletic's relegation were postponed, the latter by winning a playoff against Osasuna, champion of the Segunda División tournament.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] By 1939, when La Liga had resumed, Athletic had merged with *Aviación Nacional* of Zaragoza to become *Athletic Aviación de Madrid*.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Aviación Nacional had been founded in 1937 by three aviation officers of the Spanish Air Force.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] At that time, Real Oviedo also had its field destroyed by the war, so it was decided to give up its place to another team, and that finals spot was contested by Aviación and Osasuna, in a match in Valencia on 26 November 1939, which Aviación won 3–1.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] With the legendary Ricardo Zamora as manager, the club subsequently won their first La Liga title that season and retained the titles in 1941.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The most influential and charismatic player of these years was the captain Germán Gómez, who was signed from Racing Santander in 1939.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] He played eight consecutive seasons for the *Rojiblancos* until the 1947–48 campaign.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] From his central midfield position, he formed a legendary midfield alongside Machín and Ramón Gabilondo.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In mid-1940, a decree issued by Francisco Franco banned teams from using foreign names and the club became *Atlético Aviación de Madrid*.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In September 1940, Atlético Aviación won the first Super cup in Spanish football after beating RCD Español, the 1940 Copa del Generalísimo winners, in a two-legged game that ended in a 10–4 aggregate victory, including a 7–1 trashing in the second leg at Campo de Fútbol de Vallecas.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] On 14 December 1946, the club decided to drop the military association from its name, and shortly after, on 6 January, it settled on its current name of *Club Atlético de Madrid*.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Also in 1947, Atlético beat Real Madrid 5–0 at the *Metropolitano*, their biggest win over their cross-town rivals to date.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Under Helenio Herrera and with the help of Larbi Benbarek, Atlético won La Liga again in 1950 and 1951.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] With the departure of Herrera in 1953, the club began to slip behind Real Madrid and Barcelona and for the remainder of the 1950s were left to battle it out with Athletic Bilbao for the title of third team in Spain.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] However, during the 1960s and 1970s, Atlético Madrid seriously challenged Barcelona for the position of second team.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The 1957–58 season saw Ferdinand Daučík take charge of Atlético, where he led them to second place in La Liga.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] This resulted in Atlético qualifying for the 1958–59 European Cup since the winners, Real Madrid, were the reigning European champions.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Inspired by Brazilian centre-forward Vavá and Enrique Collar, Atlético reached the semi-finals after beating Drumcondra, CSKA Sofia and Schalke 04.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In the semi-finals, they met Real Madrid, who won the first leg 2–1 at the Santiago Bernabéu while Atlético won 1–0 at the *Metropolitano*.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The tie went to a replay and Real won 2–1 in Zaragoza.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético, however, gained their revenge when, led by former Real coach José Villalonga, they defeated Real in two successive Copa del Rey finals in 1960 and 1961.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In 1962, they won the European Cup Winners' Cup, beating Fiorentina 3–0 after a replay.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] This achievement was significant for the club, as the Cup Winners' Cup was the only major European trophy that Real Madrid never won.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The following year, the club reached the 1963 finals, but lost to English side Tottenham Hotspur 5–1.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Enrique Collar, who continued to be an influential player during this era, was now joined by the likes of midfielder Miguel Jones and midfield playmaker Adelardo.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético's best years coincided with dominant Real Madrid teams.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Between 1961 and 1980, Real Madrid dominated La Liga, winning the competition 14 times.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] During this era, only Atlético offered Real any serious challenge, winning La Liga titles in 1966, 1970, 1973 and 1977 and finishing runners-up in 1961, 1963 and 1965.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The club had further success winning the Copa del Rey on three occasions in 1965, 1972 and 1976.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In 1965, when they finished as La Liga runners-up to Real after an intense battle for the titles, Atlético became the first team to beat Real at the Bernabéu in eight years.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Significant players from this era included the now-veteran Adelardo and regular goalscorers Luis Aragonés, Javier Irureta and José Eulogio Gárate, the latter winning the *Pichichi* three times in 1969, 1970 and 1971.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In the 1970s, Atlético also recruited several Argentine players, signing Rubén Ayala, Panadero Díaz and Ramón "Cacho" Heredia as well as coach Juan Carlos Lorenzo.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Lorenzo believed in discipline, caution and disrupting the opponents' game, and although controversial, his methods proved successful—after winning La Liga in 1973, the club reached the 1974 European Cup Final.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] On the way to the Final, Atlético knocked out Galatasaray, Dinamo București, Red Star Belgrade and Celtic.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In the away leg of the semi-finals against Celtic, Atlético had Ayala, Díaz and substitute Quique all sent off during a hard-fought encounter in what was reported as one of the worst cases of cynical fouling the tournament has seen.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Because of this approach, they managed a 0–0 draw, followed by a 2–0 victory in the return leg with goals from Gárate and Adelardo.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The finals at Heysel Stadium, however, was a loss for Atlético.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Against a Bayern Munich team that included Franz Beckenbauer, Sepp Maier, Paul Breitner, Uli Hoeneß and Gerd Müller, Atlético played above themselves.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Despite missing Ayala, Díaz and Quique through suspension, they went ahead in extra-time with only seven minutes left.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Aragonés scored with a superb, curling free-kick that looked like the winner, but in the last minute of the game, Bayern defender Georg Schwarzenbeck equalized with a stunning 25-yarder that left Atlético goalkeeper Miguel Reina motionless.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In a replay back at Heysel two days later, Bayern won convincingly 4–0, with two goals each from Hoeneß and Müller.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Shortly after the defeat in the 1974 European Cup Final, Atlético appointed their veteran player Luis Aragonés as coach.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Aragonés subsequently was coach on four occasions, from 1974 to 1980, from 1982 to 1987, once again from 1991 until 1993 and finally from 2002 to 2003.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] His first success came quickly as Bayern Munich had refused to participate in the Intercontinental Cup because of fixture congestion, and as European Cup runners-up, Atlético were invited instead.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Their opponents were Independiente of Argentina and, after losing the away leg 1–0, they won the return leg 2–0 with goals from Javier Irureta and Rubén Ayala.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Aragonés subsequently led the club to further successes in the Copa del Rey in 1976 and La Liga in 1977.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] During his second spell in charge, Aragonés led the club to a runners-up finish in La Liga and a winner's medal in the Copa del Rey, both in 1985.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] He received considerable help from Hugo Sánchez, who scored 19 league goals and won the *Pichichi*.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Sánchez also scored twice in the cup finals as Atlético beat Athletic Bilbao 2–1.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Sánchez, however, only remained at the club for one season before his move across the city to Real Madrid.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Despite the loss of Sánchez, Aragonés went on to lead the club to success in the Supercopa de España in 1985 and then guided them to the European Cup Winners' Cup final in 1986.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético, however, lost their third successive European finals, this time 3–0 to Dynamo Kyiv.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético had not won La Liga for ten years and were desperate for league success.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Right away, Gil spent heavily, bringing in a number of expensive signings, most notably Portuguese winger Paulo Futre, who had just won the European Cup with Porto.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] All the spending, however, only brought in two consecutive Copa del Rey trophies in 1991 and 1992 as the league titles proved elusive.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The closest Atlético came to the La Liga trophy was the 1990–91 season when they finished runners-up by 10 points to Johan Cruyff's Barcelona.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In the process, Gil developed a ruthless reputation due to the manner in which he ran the club.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In pursuit of league success, he hired and fired a number of high-profile head coaches, including César Luis Menotti, Ron Atkinson, Javier Clemente, Tomislav Ivić, Francisco Maturana and Alfio Basile, as well as club legend Luis Aragonés.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Gil also closed down Atlético's youth academy in 1992, a move that would prove significant due to 15-year-old academy member Raúl who, as a result, went across town to later achieve worldwide fame with rivals Real Madrid.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In the 1994–95 league campaign, Atlético only avoided relegation via a draw on the last day of the season.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] This prompted another managerial change along with a wholesale squad clearance during the summer 1995 transfer window.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The next season, 1996–97, saw the club take part in the UEFA Champions League for the first time.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] With expectations and ambitions raised, the most notable summer transfer signings were striker Juan Esnáider from Real Madrid and Radek Bejbl, who was coming off a great showing for Czech Republic at Euro 1996.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Playing on two fronts, Atlético fell out of the league title contention early while, in the Champions League, they were eliminated by Ajax in extra-time in the quarter-finals.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Before the 1997–98 season, the heavy spending continued with the signings of Christian Vieri and Juninho.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] All of the success, however, produced little change in the overall Gil strategy, and although Antić survived three consecutive seasons in charge, he was replaced during the summer of 1998 with Arrigo Sacchi, who himself only remained in the managerial hot seat for less than six months.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Antić then returned briefly in early 1999 only to be replaced with Claudio Ranieri at the end of the season.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The 1999–2000 season proved disastrous for Atlético.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In December 1999, Gil and his board were suspended pending an investigation into the misuse of club funds, with government-appointed administrator José Manuel Rubí running Atlético's day-to-day operations.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] With the removal of club President Jesús Gil and his board, the players performed poorly and the club floundered.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Ranieri handed in his resignation with the club sitting 17th out of 20 in the league table and heading towards relegation.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Antić, returning for his third coaching stint, was unable to prevent the inevitable.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Despite reaching the Copa del Rey final in 2000, Atlético were relegated for the second time in 66 years.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The club spent two seasons in the Segunda División, narrowly missing out on promotion in 2000–01 season before winning the Segunda División championship in 2002.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] It was again Aragonés, in his fourth and last spell as manager of Atlético, who brought them back to the Primera División.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Aragonés also coached the team during the next season, and gave Fernando Torres his La Liga debut.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Torres came through the academy of the club and was a hot prospect in Spain; in his first season in the league, 2002–03, he scored 13 goals in 29 appearances.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In July 2003, soon after his takeover of the club, Chelsea owner Roman Abramovich offered £28 million for Torres, which was rejected by Atlético.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In the 2003–04 season, Torres continued his success as he scored 19 league goals in 35 appearances, making him the joint third-highest scorer in the league.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Torres had been at Atlético since the age of 11 and his precocious talent led to him becoming the club's youngest ever captain at the age of just 19.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In 2006, Atlético signed Portuguese midfielders Costinha and Maniche, as well as Argentine forward Sergio Agüero.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In July 2007, Torres left the club for Liverpool for €38 million, while Luis García signed for the club at the same time in an unrelated transfer.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The club also bought Uruguay international and former European Golden Boot and *Pichichi* winners Diego Forlán for roughly €21 million from Villarreal.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Other additions included Portuguese winger Simão Sabrosa from Benfica for €20 million and winger José Antonio Reyes from Arsenal for €12 million.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In July 2007, the Atlético board reached an agreement with the City of Madrid to sell the land where their stadium was located and move the club to the City-owned Olympic Stadium.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The stadium changed hands in 2016 and was bought by the club for €30.4 million.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Madrid had applied to host the 2016 Olympic Games, losing out to Rio de Janeiro.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The 2007–08 season proved to be the most successful season for the club in the past decade.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The team reached the round of 32 in the UEFA Cup, where they were defeated by Bolton Wanderers.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] They also reached the quarter-finals round of the Copa del Rey, where they were beaten by eventual champions Valencia.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] More significantly, the team finished the league season in fourth place, qualifying for the UEFA Champions League for the first time since the 1996–97 season.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] On 3 February 2009, Javier Aguirre was dismissed from his post as manager after a poor start to the season, going without a win in six games.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] He later claimed that this was not accurate, and that he had left by mutual termination rather than through sacking.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] There was public outrage after his dismissal, many believing he was not the cause of Atlético's problems, namely player Diego Forlán.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] He backed his former manager and said that, "Dismissing Javier was the easy way out, but he was not the cause of our problems.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The players are to blame because we have not been playing well and we have been committing a lot of errors." This led to the appointment of Abel Resino as Atlético's new manager.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético's success continued in the latter half of the season when they placed fourth once again in the league table, securing a position in the playoff round of the UEFA Champions League.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Striker Diego Forlán was crowned with the *Pichichi* and also won the European Golden Shoe after scoring 32 goals for Atlético that season.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético saw this domestic success as an opportunity to reinforce their squad for the upcoming Champions League season.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] They replaced veteran goalkeeper Leo Franco with David de Gea from the youth ranks and signed promising youngster Sergio Asenjo from Real Valladolid.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético also acquired Real Betis defender and Spanish international Juanito on a free transfer.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Despite pressure from big clubs to sell star players Agüero and Forlán, Atlético remained committed to keeping their strong attacking base in the hopes for a successful new season.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The 2009–10 season, however, began poorly with many defeats and goals conceded.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] On 21 October, Atlético were hammered 4–0 by English club Chelsea in the Champions League group stage.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] This defeat led Atlético's management to announce that manager Abel Resino had to leave.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] After failing to sign Danish former footballer Michael Laudrup, Atlético Madrid announced that the new manager for the rest of the season would be Quique Sánchez Flores.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] With the arrival of Sánchez Flores as coach in October 2009, Atlético improved in many of their competition.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético continued to lag somewhat in La Liga during the 2009–10 season, finishing in ninth position, but managed to finish third in their 2009–10 UEFA Champions League group stage and subsequently entered the Europa League in the round of 32.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético went on to win the Europa League, beating English teams Liverpool in the semi-finals and eventually Fulham in the finals held at HSH Nordbank Arena in Hamburg on 12 May 2010.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Diego Forlán scored twice, the second being an extra-time winner in the 116th minute, as Atlético won 2–1.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] It was the first time since the 1961–62 European Cup Winners' Cup that Atlético had claimed a European titles.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] They also reached the Copa del Rey finals on 19 May 2010, where they faced Sevilla, but lost 2–0 at the Camp Nou in Barcelona.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] By winning the Europa League, they qualified for the 2010 UEFA Super Cup against Inter Milan, winner of the 2009–10 UEFA Champions League.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The match was played at the Stade Louis II, Monaco on 27 August 2010.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético won 2–0 with goals from José Antonio Reyes and Agüero, making it the club's first win in the UEFA Super Cup.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético had a comparatively disappointing 2010–11 season, finishing only seventh in the League and being eliminated in the quarter-finals of the Copa del Rey and the group stage of the Europa League.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] This ultimately led to the departure of manager Sánchez Flores before the conclusion of the season, who was replaced with ex-Sevilla manager Gregorio Manzano.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] On 23 December 2011, Atlético appointed their former Argentine player, Diego Simeone, as manager in place of Manzano.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The club were in a period of uncertainty, having appointed five managers in less than three years and allowing young talents, namely Agüero and de Gea, to leave for the Premier League.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The team was sitting 10th in La Liga at the time of Simeone's appointment, after losing four of their last five games.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The appointment of Simeone was seen as a risk, who was relatively inexperienced and previously only had European managerial experience with Italian underdogs Catania.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] However, he swiftly transformed Atlético into a formidable force.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] As a player, Simeone was known as a fierce, all-action midfielder; he brought the same relentless, win-at-all-costs mentality to Atlético as manager.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] His focus was on building a strong defence, anchored by teenage Chelsea loanee goalkeeper Thibaut Courtois and Uruguayan centre-back Diego Godín.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The results were immediate, as Simeone's first six games in charge featured six clean sheets.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] According to Spanish football writer Andy West, Atlético fans came to quickly to embrace Simeone, especially in light of his role as a pivotal player in their 1995-96 league and cup double.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Simeone led Atlético to their second Europa League win in the three years since its creation; Atlético beat Athletic Bilbao 3–0 in the final on 9 May 2012 at National Arena in Bucharest with two goals from Radamel Falcao and one from Diego.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] By winning the Europa League again, Atlético qualified for the 2012 UEFA Super Cup against Chelsea, winners of the previous season's Champions League.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The game was played at the Stade Louis II, Monaco on 31 August 2012; Atlético won 4–1, including a hat-trick by Falcao in the first half.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] On 17 May 2013, Atlético beat Real Madrid 2–1 in the Copa del Rey final in a tense match where both teams finished with ten men.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] This ended a 14-year and 25-match winless streak in the Madrid derby.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The 2012–13 season saw the club finish with three trophies in a little over a year.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] On 17 May 2014, a 1–1 draw at the Camp Nou against Barcelona secured the La Liga title for Atlético, their first since 1996, and the first titles since 2003–04 not won by Barcelona or Real Madrid.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] One week later, Atlético faced city rivals Real Madrid in their first Champions League final since 1974, and the first played between two sides from the same city.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] They took a first-half lead through Godín and led until the third minute of injury time, when Sergio Ramos headed in an equaliser from a corner; the match went to extra time, and Real ultimately won 4–1.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Antoine Griezmann, who had a standout season in La Liga and featured at the 2014 FIFA World Cup, joined Atlético from Real Sociedad on 28 July 2014.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] During his first stint with the club, Griezmann was Atlético's top scorer for five consecutive seasons.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] He established himself as a world-class player at Atlético, also shining on the international stage as he finished as the top scorer at UEFA Euro 2016 and earned the tournament's best player award.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] That same year, he placed third in the Ballon d'Or rankings, behind Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético reached a second Champions League final in three seasons in 2015–16, again facing Real Madrid, and lost on penalties after a 1–1 draw.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The club played their last home game at the Vicente Calderón Stadium on 21 May 2017, thereby moving to a new home, the refurbished Wanda Metropolitano in eastern Madrid.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In 2018, they won their third Europa League title in nine years by beating Marseille 3–0 in the finals at the Stade de Lyon in Lyon, courtesy of a brace from Griezmann and a goal from club captain Gabi in what would be his last match for the club.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético also won another UEFA Super Cup after beating Real Madrid 4–2 at the outset of the following season at the Lilleküla Arena in Tallinn.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] On 25 September 2020, Atlético signed Luis Suárez from Barcelona.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] One of the world's best strikers, Suárez made a dramatic impact at the club, as he played a pivotal role in their unexpected La Liga title triumph, seven years after the 2013–14 win.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] He scored 17 goals in his first 19 La Liga matches, helping Atlético establish a 10-point lead by January.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Although the team wavered later in the season, Suárez's relentless competitive drive proved decisive, as he netted crucial goals in the final two games to secure the title.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The final game of the title-winning season was on 22 May 2021, a 2–1 win at the José Zorrilla Stadium against Valladolid.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] On April 16, 2024, the team qualified to the 2025 FIFA Club World Cup for first time in club's history, despite being eliminated in the 2023–24 Champions League, as Barcelona were also eliminated, and Atlético were the higher ranked Spanish club in the UEFA four-year ranking.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] On 12 March 2026, Atletico Madrid announced that Apollo Sports Capital had completed the acquisition of a majority stake in the club.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Real Madrid and Atlético Madrid are clubs with contrasting identities and different fates.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Historically, Real Madrid have long been seen as the establishment club.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] On the other side, Atlético Madrid were always characterized by a *sentimiento de rebeldía*, a sense of rebellion.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] They were associated with the military airforce (renamed Atlético Aviación), until the regime's preferences moved towards Real Madrid in the 1950s.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Certainly, the dictatorial state sought to make political capital out of Real Madrid's European Cup trophies at a time when Spain was internationally isolated; "Real Madrid are the best embassy we ever had", said Franco's foreign minister Fernando Maria de Castiella.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Such perceptions have had an important impact on the city's footballing identities, tapping into the collective consciousness.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Until recently, Atlético Madrid had struggled significantly in the derby, carrying a 14-year winless streak into the 2012–13 season.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] This spell ended, however, on 17 May 2013 after Atlético beat their city rivals 2–1 at the Santiago Bernabéu in the 2013 Copa del Rey finals, and continued on 29 September 2013 when they won a 1–0 victory, again at the Bernabéu.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The two faced each other in the 2014 and 2016 UEFA Champions League finals, with Real Madrid winning both matches.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Although less famous than the Derbi Madrileño, a historic rivalry exists between Atlético Madrid and Barcelona, which is also considered one of the "Classics" of Spanish football.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] However, by tradition and current affairs, the greatest rivalry is that which exists with its "merengues" neighbors.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético has played at the European stage regularly since its 1958–59 European Cup debut, subsequently entering the UEFA Cup Winners' Cup (1961–62), the Inter-Cities Fairs Cup (1963–64), the UEFA Cup (1971–72) and the UEFA Super Cup (2009–10).
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Starting with the 1999–2000 relegation, Atlético did not qualify for European competition for seven years, but from the 2007–08 season, it has taken part in either the Champions League or the UEFA Europa League every year, enjoying success in both competition.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Highest-ranked eliminated team in case of qualification, lowest-ranked qualified team in case of elimination.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Spanish teams are limited to three players without EU citizenship.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The squad list includes only the principal nationality of each player; several non-European players on the squad have dual citizenship with an EU country.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Also, players from the ACP countries in Africa, the Caribbean, and the Pacific that are signatories to the Cotonou Agreement are not counted against non-EU quotas due to the Kolpak ruling.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Note: Flags indicate national team as defined under FIFA eligibility rules; some limited exceptions apply.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Players may hold more than one non-FIFA nationality.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In 1992, Spain’s new Sports Law forced all First and Second Division football clubs to convert into sports limited companies.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Atlético Madrid, led by president Jesús Gil since 1987, was teetering on the edge of bankruptcy.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] On the final day to comply, the club scraped together enough capital to meet the requirements.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Days later, Gil and then–vice president Enrique Cerezo quietly seized control of the club without paying a single *peseta*.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The maneuver was fraudulent, but it would take seven years for the so‑called *Caso Atlético* to reach court.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In 1999, Gil, Cerezo, and then‑director general Miguel Ángel Gil were charged with fraud and embezzlement.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The courts confirmed the crimes — but the statute of limitations had already expired.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] As a result, the shares remained in their hands, and the club’s ownership structure, born of a legal sleight of hand, was never undone.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] Since 2003, Cerezo has served as the club’s president, while Miguel Ángel Gil Marín — son of former president Jesús Gil — has held the role of chief executive officer.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In 2015, the Chinese conglomerate Wanda Group purchased a 17% stake in Atlético Madrid.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] In 2017, Quantum Pacific Group, owned by Israeli billionaire Idan Ofer, acquired a 15% stake in the club.
[src:home-sports/atlético-madrid-p01] The following year, Wanda Group sold its entire holding to Quantum Pacific Group, raising the latter's ownership to 32%.
